title:
A census of graph-drawing algorithms based on generalized transversal
  structures

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We present two graph drawing algorithms based on the recently defined grandSchnyder woods, which are a far-reaching generalization of the classical Schnyder woods. The first is a straight-line drawing algorithm for plane graphs with faces of degree 3 and 4 with no separating 3 -cycle, while the second is a rectangular drawing algorithm for the dual of such plane graphs.

In our algorithms, the coordinates of the vertices are defined in a global manner, based on the underlying grand-Schnyder woods. The grand-Schnyder woods and drawings are computed in linear time.

When specializing our algorithms to special classes of plane graphs, we recover the following known algorithms:

- He's algorithm for rectangular drawing of 3-valent plane graphs, based on transversal structures,
- Fusy's algorithm for the straight-line drawing of triangulations of the square, based on transversal structures,
- Bernardi and Fusy's algorithm for the orthogonal drawing of 4-valent plane graphs, based on 2-orientations,
- Barrière and Huemer's algorithm for the straight-line drawing of quadrangulations, based on separating decompositions.
Our contributions therefore provide a unifying perspective on a large family of graph drawing algorithms that were originally defined on different classes of plane graphs and were based on seemingly different combinatorial structures.

## 1. InTRODUCTION

In the rich literature on graph drawing algorithms (see for instance [BETT99, NR04] and references therein), two of the most classical and popular types of drawings are straight-line drawings (in which edges are represented by straight-line segments) and orthogonal drawings (where edges are represented by a sequence of axis-aligned segments).

1.1. New drawing algorithms based on grand-Schnyder woods. In this article we present two new drawing algorithms: a straight-line drawing algorithm for simple plane graphs with faces of degree 3 or 4 with no separating cycle of length 3 , and an orthogonal drawing algorithm for their duals. Graph drawings obtained using these algorithms are shown in Figure 1. In these algorithms, the coordinates of the vertices are defined globally, either in terms of face-counts in certain regions or in terms of increasing functions over some bipolar orientations. The combinatorial structures and the drawings can be computed in linear time.

Our drawing algorithms are based on a recently discovered class of combinatorial structures [BFL24]. These structures are called grand-Schnyder structures in honor of their relation to the classical Schnyder woods underlying a most famous drawing algorithm [Sch90]. Precisely, for every integer $d \geq 3$, a class of combinatorial structures called $d$-grand-Schnyder ( $d-G S$ for short), was defined for $d$-maps, that is, connected plane graphs such that the outer face has degree $d$ and inner faces have degree at most $d$. It was shown in [BFL24] that a $d$-map admits a $d$-GS structure if and only if its non-facial cycles have length at least $d$. The classical Schnyder woods correspond to 3-GS structures on triangulations.

In this article, the algorithms are based on 4-GS structures. Interestingly, when specializing 4-GS structures to the case of the triangulations of the square, one recovers a combinatorial structure used in another classical graph drawing algorithm, namely the regular edge labelings used by He to define a rectangular drawing algorithm for 3 -valent plane graphs [He93]. Since then, regular edge labelings have been rediscovered and popularized under the name transversal structures which we shall adopt in the present article. In a different direction, when specializing 4-GS structures to quadrangulations one recovers the separating decompositions (or equivalently, 2-orientations) which have also found applications to graph drawing algorithms: straight-line drawings and orthogonal drawings [BH12, BF12], as well as visibility representations and segment contact representations [RT86, TT86, TT89].

As we will later explain, our orthogonal drawing algorithm interpolates between He's algorithm [He93] (for 3-valent plane graphs) and Bernardi and Fusy's algorithm [BF12] (for 4 -valent plane graphs), while our straight-line drawing algorithm interpolates between Fusy's algorithm [Fus09] (for triangulations) and Barrière and Huemer's algorithm [BH12] (for quadrangulations). This reveals the deep hidden commonality between these 4 algorithms (in addition to relating them to other Schnyder-wood based algorithms [Sch90, Fel01]). Our proofs are also uniform, and make use of a simple local planarity criteria which could be of independent interest (Lemma 3.7).

Before describing our results further, we give a quick review of the 4 drawing algorithms in [BH12, BF12, Fus09, He93].
1.2. A review of four classical graph-drawing algorithms. In this subsection we review the following graph drawing algorithms:

- the straight-line drawing algorithm for irreducible triangulations of the square due to Fusy [Fus09], and the (bendless) orthogonal drawing algorithm for their duals due to He [He93],
- the straight-line drawing algorithm for simple quadrangulations due to Barrière and Huemer [BH12], and the orthogonal drawing algorithm for their duals due to Bernardi and Fusy [BF12].
We start by defining the combinatorial structures underlying these algorithms: transversal structures and separating decompositions.

We call planar map a planar drawing of a connected planar graph, considered up to continuous deformation. A triangulation of the square is a planar map such that every inner face has degree 3 , while the outer face has degree 4 . Such a planar map is called irreducible if it

![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)

Figure 2. Left: The local conditions (at inner vertices and at outer vertices) for transversal structures. Right: Example of a transversal structure on a triangulation of the square.
has no cycle of length less than 4 except for the contour of the inner faces. It was shown by He [He93] that irreducible triangulations of the square can be endowed with some combinatorial structures that he named regular edge-labelings. These structures were later rediscovered by Fusy [Fus09], who used the name transversal structures that we adopt below. Consider an irreducible triangulation of the square $G$, with its outer vertices labeled $v_{1}, v_{2}, v_{3}, v_{4}$ in clockwise order. A transversal structure for $G$ is an orientation and bicoloration of its inner edges - in blue and red - satisfying the local conditions shown in Figure 2:
(1) At each inner vertex the incident edges form 4 groups in clockwise order: outgoing red, outgoing blue, incoming red, incoming blue.
(2) The edges incident to the outer vertices $v_{1}, v_{2}, v_{3}, v_{4}$ are respectively outgoing red, outgoing blue, incoming red, and incoming blue.

It is known that these local conditions imply the global condition that the spanning subgraph $G_{r}$ formed by the red edges and the 4 outer edges directed from $v_{1}$ to $v_{3}$ is an acyclic orientation with a unique source $v_{1}$ and a unique sink $v_{3}$; and similarly the spanning subgraph $G_{b}$ formed by the blue edges and the 4 outer edges directed from $v_{2}$ to $v_{4}$ is an acyclic orientation with a unique source $v_{2}$ and a unique sink $v_{4}$. See Figure 2 for an example.
![img-2.jpeg](img-2.jpeg)

Figure 3. Left: The local conditions, at inner vertices and at outer vertices, for separating decompositions. Right: Example of a separating decomposition on a simple quadrangulation.

A (simple) quadrangulation is a planar map (without loops nor double edges) such that every face has degree 4. It was shown in [DFOdMR95] that simple quadrangulations can be endowed with combinatorial structures called separating decompositions. Consider a simple quadrangulation $G$ with its outer vertices labeled $v_{1}, v_{2}, v_{3}, v_{4}$ in clockwise order, and consider the proper bicoloration of its vertices in black and white such that $v_{1}$ is black (quadrangulations are bipartite). A separating decomposition for $G$ is an orientation and bicoloration of its inner edges - in blue and orange - satisfying the local conditions shown in Figure 3:
(1) At every black (resp. white) inner vertex there is a single outgoing blue edge $e$ and a single outgoing orange edge $e^{\prime}$, and all the incident edges between $e$ and $e^{\prime}$ in clockwise order are blue (resp. orange) while all the incident edges between $e^{\prime}$ and $e$ are orange (resp. blue).
(2) The edges incident to the outer vertices $v_{1}, v_{2}, v_{3}, v_{4}$ are all incoming; they are orange at $v_{1}, v_{2}$ and blue at $v_{3}, v_{4}$.
It is shown in [DFOdMR95] that the subgraph $T_{o}$ formed by the inner vertices, the orange edges, and the outer edge $\left(v_{1}, v_{2}\right)$ is a tree, with edges oriented toward $\left\{v_{1}, v_{2}\right\}$; by convention it is considered as rooted at $v_{2}$. Similarly the subgraph $T_{b}$ formed by the inner vertices, the blue edges and the outer edge $\left(v_{3}, v_{4}\right)$ is a tree, rooted at $v_{4}$.

The two combinatorial structures described above have been used to define straight-line drawing algorithms using face-counting operations. These algorithms were introduced respectively in [Fus09] for transversal structures, and in [BH12] for separating decompositions. We will now describe these algorithms before turning to the dual picture.
![img-3.jpeg](img-3.jpeg)

Figure 4. The straight-line drawing obtained using the transversal structure shown in Figure 2. The blue and red separating paths are shown for the circled vertex $v$. For this vertex, the blue path $P_{b}(v)$ has 4 faces on its right in the blue map, and the red path has 5 faces on its left in the red map. Accordingly, $v$ has coordinates $(5,4)$ in the drawing. Placing similarly all the inner vertices yields the planar straight-line drawing shown on the right. Since the red and blue maps have 10 and 9 inner faces respectively, the grid has size $10 \times 9$.

We start by describing the drawing algorithm from [Fus09] which is illustrated in Figure 4. Let $G$ be an irreducible triangulation of the square endowed with a transversal structure. For every inner vertex $v$ of $G$ we will define some blue and red separating paths, represented in Figure 4, which are used to determine the placement of $v$. The leftmost outgoing blue path of an inner vertex $v$ is the path $P_{\text {blue }}^{\text {out }}(v)$ starting at $v$ and taking the leftmost outgoing blue edge at each step until reaching $v_{4}$, while the rightmost incoming blue path is the path $P_{\text {blue }}^{\text {in }}(v)$ starting at $v$ and taking the rightmost incoming blue edge at each step until reaching $v_{2}$. We use the notation $P^{-}$for the reversal of a directed path $P$, and define the blue separating path at $v$ as the blue path $P_{\text {blue }}(v)=P_{\text {blue }}^{\text {out }}(v) \cup P_{\text {blue }}^{\text {in }}(v)^{-}$going from $v_{2}$ to $v_{4}$. We define similarly

the leftmost outgoing red path $P_{\text {red }}^{\text {out }}(v)$ (going from $v$ to $v_{3}$ ), the rightmost incoming red path $P_{\text {red }}^{\text {in }}(v)$ (going from $v$ to $v_{1}$ ), and the red separating path $P_{\text {red }}(v)=P_{\text {red }}^{\text {out }}(v) \cup P_{\text {red }}^{\text {in }}(v)^{-}$. In the straight-line drawing of $G$ given by [Fus09], the vertices are placed on a grid of size $f_{r} \times f_{b}$, where $f_{r}, f_{b}$ are the numbers of inner faces in the red and blue maps $G_{r}, G_{b}$ :

- the outer vertices of $G$ are placed at the 4 corners of the grid with $v_{1}$ at the origin,
- each inner vertex $v$ is placed at $\left(x_{v}, y_{v}\right)$, where $x_{v}$ is the number of inner faces of $G_{r}$ on the left of $P_{\text {red }}(v)$, and $y_{v}$ is the number of inner faces of $G_{b}$ on the right of $P_{\text {blue }}(v)$. An example is given in Figure 4.
![img-4.jpeg](img-4.jpeg)

Figure 5. The straight-line drawing obtained using the separating decomposition shown in Figure 3. The even (resp. odd) separating path of the circled vertex is shown, with 5 faces on its left (resp. 7 faces on its right). Accordingly the circled vertex has coordinates $(5,7)$ in the drawing. Placing similarly all the inner vertices yields the planar straight-line drawing shown on the right. Since there are 11 inner faces, the grid has size $11 \times 11$.

Next we describe the algorithm from [BH12], which is illustrated in Figure 5. Let $G$ be a simple quadrangulation endowed with a separating decomposition. For each inner vertex $v$ we define an odd and an even separating path as illustrated in Figure 5. For all $i \in\{1,2,3,4\}$ we define $P_{i}(v)$ as the directed path from $v$ to $v_{i+3}$ obtained by following the outgoing arcs as follows:

- for $i=1$ (resp. $i=3$ ) we follow the outgoing blue (resp. orange) arc at every vertex,
- for $i=2$ (resp. $i=4$ ) we follow the outgoing blue (resp. orange) arc at every black vertex, and the outgoing orange (resp. blue) arc at every white vertex.
In the above definition of $P_{i}(v)$ the $\operatorname{arcs}\left(v_{2}, v_{3}\right)$ and $\left(v_{3}, v_{4}\right)$ are blue, and the $\operatorname{arcs}\left(v_{4}, v_{1}\right)$ and $\left(v_{1}, v_{2}\right)$ are orange. It is shown in [FHKO11] that with these conventions, the path $P_{i}(v)$ is always well-defined and ends at $v_{i+3}$ for all $i$ [FHKO11]. The odd separating path at $v$ is the path $P_{o}(v):=P_{1}(v) \cup P_{3}(v)^{-}$going from $v_{2}$ to $v_{4}$, while the even separating path at $v$ is the path $P_{e}(v):=P_{4}(v) \cup P_{2}(v)^{-}$going from $v_{1}$ to $v_{3}$. The separating paths are always simple paths as shown in [FHKO11]. In the straight-line drawing of $G$ given by [BH12], the vertices are placed on a grid of size $f \times f$, where $f$ is the number of inner faces:
- the outer vertices of $G$ are placed at the 4 corners of the grid with $v_{1}$ at the origin,
- each inner vertex $v$ is placed at $\left(x_{v}, y_{v}\right)$, where $x_{v}$ is the number of inner faces of $G$ on the left of $P_{e}(v)$, and $y_{v}$ is the number of inner faces of $G$ on the right of $P_{o}(v)$.
An example is given in Figure 5.
Let us highlight the similarity between the algorithms in [Fus09] and [BH12]. As already noted in [BH12] (building upon the 0,1-labelings of [FHKO11]), there is a natural way to label the inner corners of a separating decomposition with labels in $\{1,2,3,4\}$ using the rule

represented in Figure 6, and the paths $P_{1}(v), \ldots, P_{4}(v)$ associated to an inner vertex $v$ can be defined in terms of this labeling: at each inner vertex the path $P_{i}(v)$ takes the outgoing edge separating the labels $i$ and $i+1$. Similarly, there is a natural way to label the inner corners of a transversal structure using the rules represented in Figure 6, and the blue and red separating paths can be defined in terms of these labelings: at each inner vertex the path $P_{\text {blue }}^{\text {out }}(v)$ (resp. $\left.P_{\text {red }}^{\text {in }}(v), P_{\text {blue }}^{\text {in }}(v), P_{\text {red }}^{\text {out }}(v)\right)$ takes the edge separating the labels 1 and 2 (resp. 2 and 3,3 and 4,4 and 1 ).

Figure 6. Left: Corner labeling associated to a transversal structure (rule for defining the labels around outer and inner vertices, and an example). Right: Corner labeling associated to a separating decomposition (rule for defining the labels around outer vertices and around black and white inner vertices, and an example).

We now turn our attention to the dual picture, and review two orthogonal drawing algorithms based on the same pair of combinatorial structures [BF12, He93]. An orthogonal drawing of a planar graph $G^{\prime}$ is a drawing such that each edge is a sequence of axis-aligned segments, a bend being a turning point on an edge. An orthogonal drawing is called one-bend if every edge has at most one bend. All orthogonal drawing algorithms to be reviewed and introduced in the paper produce one-bend drawings (upon not drawing the root vertex, see below).
![img-6.jpeg](img-6.jpeg)

Figure 7. Orthogonal drawing from [BF12] obtained using the (dual of the) separating decomposition shown in Figure 3. The odd and even separating paths of the circled vertex $v$ are indicated. The even path $P_{e}^{\prime}(v)$ has 2 faces on its left, while the odd path $P_{o}^{\prime}(v)$ has 6 faces on its right, hence the circled vertex has coordinates $(2,6)$ in the drawing. Placing similarly all the dual vertices (excluding $v_{\infty}$ ) yields the orthogonal drawing shown on the right.

We first describe orthogonal drawing algorithm from [BF12] for the dual of simple quadrangulations. Let $G$ be a simple quadrangulation, let $G^{*}$ be the dual of $G$, and let $v_{\infty}$ be the

vertex of $G^{*}$ dual to the outer face of $G$. We call $v_{\infty}$ the root vertex of $G^{*}$. The drawing of $G^{\prime}:=G^{*} \backslash v_{\infty}$ is again based on a face-counting procedure. For $i \in\{1,2,3,4\}$ we define $e_{i}^{*}$ as the edge of $G^{*}$ dual to the outer edge $\left\{v_{i}, v_{i+1}\right\}$ of $G$, and we let $v_{i}^{*}$ be the non-root endpoint of $e_{i}^{*}$. Recall that, given a separating decomposition of $G$, one can associate some labels to the inner corners of $G$ as indicated in Figure 6. By duality, this gives a labeling of the corners of $G^{*}$ not incident to $v_{\infty}$. This labeling is such that the labels $1,2,3,4$ appear in clockwise order around each non-root vertex. See Figure 7 for an example. For $i \in\{1,2,3,4\}$, let $P_{i}^{\prime}(v)$ be the path starting at $v$ and taking the edge separating the corners of labels $i$ and $i+1$ at each vertex, until reaching $v_{i}^{*}$. The even separating path at $v$ is the simple directed path $P_{e}^{\prime}(v):=P_{2}^{\prime}(v) \cup P_{4}^{\prime}(v)^{-}$ from $v_{4}^{*}$ to $v_{2}^{*}$ (where we again use the notation $P^{-}$to indicate the path obtained by reversing $P)$. The odd separating path at $v$ is the path $P_{o}^{\prime}(v):=P_{3}^{\prime}(v) \cup P_{1}^{\prime}(v)^{-}$from $v_{1}^{*}$ to $v_{3}^{*}$. In the orthogonal drawing of $G^{\prime}$ from [BF12], the coordinates $(x, y)$ of each non-root vertex $v$ are such that $x$ (resp. $y$ ) is the number of inner faces of $G^{\prime}$ on the left of $P_{e}^{\prime}(v)$ (resp. on the right of $\left.P_{o}^{\prime}(v)\right)$. Each edge is then drawn as the union of two axis-aligned segments in the unique way such that, at each vertex $v$, the path $P_{1}^{\prime}(v)$ (resp. $P_{2}^{\prime}(v), P_{3}^{\prime}(v), P_{4}^{\prime}(v)$ ) leaves $v$ toward the left (resp. top, right, bottom). Equivalently, the corner of label 1 (resp. 2,3,4) occupies the south-west (resp. north-west, north-east, south-east) quadrant at $v$. If $G^{\prime}$ has $n$ inner faces, then the grid size is $n \times n$. An example is given in Figure 7.
![img-7.jpeg](img-7.jpeg)

Figure 8. Rectangular drawing obtained using increasing functions on the transversal structure shown in Figure 2. The increasing functions of $G_{b}$ and $G_{r}$ are indicated on the left, and the resulting rectangular drawing of $G^{\prime}$ is shown on the right.

Last but not least, we recall the rectangular drawing algorithm from [He93] based on transversal structures. Recall that a rectangular drawing is an orthogonal drawing, such that edges have no bend, and all faces (including the outer face) have a rectangular shape. Let $G$ be an irreducible triangulation of the square, let $G^{*}$ be its dual, and let $v_{\infty}$ be the vertex of $G^{*}$ dual to the outer face of $G$. We consider a transversal structure of $G$, and define a rectangular drawing of $G^{\prime}:=G^{*} \backslash v_{\infty}$ using some "increasing functions" on the faces of the blue and red maps, as represented in Figure 8. An increasing function for $G_{r}$ (resp. $G_{b}$ ) is an assignment of values in $\mathbb{R}$ to the inner faces such that every inner edge has a smaller (resp. larger) label on the left side than on the right side. Every vertex $v \in G^{\prime}$ is dual to a triangular inner face $f$ of $G$ which is contained in a face $f_{r}(v)$ of $G_{r}$ and in a face $f_{b}(v)$ of $G_{b}$. In the rectangular drawing of $G^{\prime}$ from [He93], the coordinates $(x, y)$ of $v$ are such that $x$ (resp. $y$ ) is the label of the face $f_{r}(v)$ (resp. $f_{b}(v)$ ). If face-labels are in $\mathbb{N}$, then one obtains a rectangular drawing on a grid. The choice of increasing function for $G_{r}$ (resp. $G_{b}$ ) yielding the smallest grid-width (resp. grid-height) is the one where the label of the leftmost (resp. rightmost) inner face is 0 , and the

label of each other inner face is 1 plus the maximum of the labels of the faces that are adjacent from the left (resp. right); equivalently, each face is labeled by the length of a longest path in the dual bipolar orientation. This optimal choice of increasing functions is used in Figure 8.
1.3. Outline of the article. In this article we present two new drawing algorithms that make use of the grand-Schnyder woods introduced in [BFL24]. Our straight line drawing algorithm applies to the class of 4 -adapted maps, which are the planar maps such that the outer face has degree 4 , the inner faces have degree at most 4 and the non-facial cycles have length at least 4. Our orthogonal drawing algorithm applies to the dual of 4 -adapted maps.

It was shown in [BFL24] that any 4-adapted map admits a 4 -grand-Schnyder wood (or4-GS wood for short), which can be computed in linear time. The definition of 4-GS woods will be given in Section 2. Note that the irreducible triangulations of the square are the 4-adapted maps having only inner faces of degree 3 , while the simple quadrangulations are the 4 -adapted maps having inner faces of degree 4 . Hence, irreducible triangulations of the square and simple quadrangulations form two subclasses of 4 -adapted maps. Moreover, as we will explain in Section 2.2, the transversal structures of a triangulation of the square are in bijection with the 4 -GS woods of that triangulation. As for separating decompositions, they correspond bijectively to a special class of 4 -GS woods of quadrangulations satisfying some parity conditions (the even 4-GS woods). So the concept of 4-GS woods allows one to interpolate between the concept of transversal structures used in [Fus09, He93] and the concept of separating decompositions used in [BH12, BF12].

Regarding straight-line drawings, we present a "face-counting" algorithm for 4-adapted maps, where the coordinates of each vertex are determined as the number of faces in certain "regions" associated to that vertex. When specialized to irreducible triangulations of the square or to simple quadrangulations, the face counting algorithm yields the two algorithms from [Fus09] and from [BH12] respectively. ${ }^{1}$ We then present a more general straight-line drawing algorithm for 4 -adapted maps, where the coordinates of each vertex are obtained using increasing functions on some bipolar orientations associated to the 4 -GS wood. We show that the increasing function algorithm can be performed in linear time, and that it leads to a grid size that is less or equal to the grid size of the face-counting algorithm. We also discuss some strategies for further decreasing the grid-size.

Regarding orthogonal drawings, we first give a "face-counting" algorithm for the dual of 4adapted maps (where the coordinates of each vertex are defined as the number of faces in certain "regions" associated to that vertex). We then present a more general "increasing function" drawing algorithm. The face-counting algorithm recovers the algorithm from [BF12] when applied to the dual of quadrangulations, while the increasing-function algorithm recovers the algorithm from [He93] when applied to the dual of triangulations. We show that the increasing function algorithm can be performed in linear time, and we then discuss strategies to minimize the number of bends and to decrease the grid-size. The orthogonal drawings produced by our algorithm are right-chiral: an edge starting at a 3 -valent vertex is either straight or has a right-bend (in particular edges between 3 -valent vertices are straight). We show that the dual of a 4 -map admits a right-chiral drawing if and only if it is 4 -adapted, in which case we give an algorithm to construct a right-chiral drawing achieving the minimum number of bends possible.

The article is organized as follows. In Section 2 we define the combinatorial structures relevant for our drawing algorithms: 4-GS labelings, 4-GS woods, and some associated bipolar orientations (in the primal and in the dual). In Section 3 we present our straight-line drawing algorithms for 4-adapted maps: we start by presenting a face-counting algorithm (Section 3.1)

# 2. Combinatorial Structures 

In this section we lay out some basic definitions about planar maps, and then define the combinatorial structures which underlie our drawing algorithms. These combinatorial structures have been introduced in [BFL24] under the name grand-Schnyder structures. Precisely, we will be using 4 -grand-Schnyder structures and their duals.
2.1. Planar maps. Our graphs are finite and undirected. A simple graph is a graph without loops nor multiple edges. A planar map is a connected planar graph drawn in the plane without edge crossing, considered up to continuous deformation. A corner of a planar map is the sector delimited by 2 consecutive edges around a vertex. A vertex or face has degree $k$ if it is incident to $k$ corners. An arc of a graph is an edge together with a chosen orientation of this edge (so each edge gives rise to two opposite arcs). The endpoints of an arc $a$ are called the initial and terminal vertices of $a$. We write $a=(u, v)$ to indicate that $u$ and $v$ are the initial and terminal vertices of the arc $a$ respectively. The infinite face of a planar map is called the outer face, while the others are called inner faces. We also call outer the vertices, edges, arcs and corners incident to the outer face, and inner the others.

A 3,4-angulation of the square is a planar map such that the inner faces have degree 3 or 4 , and the outer face has degree 4 and is incident to 4 distinct outer vertices. We canonically denote the outer vertices of such a planar map by $v_{1}, v_{2}, v_{3}, v_{4}$, in clockwise order around the outer face. A 3,4 -angulation of the square is called adapted if any simple cycle which is not the contour of a face has length at least 4 . Note that adapted 3,4 -angulations are necessarily simple. Note also that a planar map with every face of degree 4 is adapted if and only if its girth is 4 (where girth means the minimal length of cycles).

Recall that the dual $G^{*}$ of a planar map $G$ is obtained as follows:

- we draw a vertex $v_{f}$ of $G^{*}$ inside every face $f$ of $G$ and call $v_{f}$ the dual vertex of $f$,
- and we draw an edge $e^{*}$ of $G^{*}$ connecting $v_{f}$ and $v_{g}$ across each edge $e$ separating the faces $f$ and $g$ of $G$, and call $e^{*}$ the dual edge of the primal edge $e$.
The root vertex of $G^{*}$ is the vertex $v_{\infty}$ dual to the outer face of $G$.
If $G$ is a 3,4 -angulation of the square, then its dual graph $G^{*}$ is a planar map having vertices of degree 3 or 4 , with a designated root vertex $v_{\infty}$ of degree 4 . We call such a map a rooted 3,4-map. A rooted 3,4 -map $G^{*}$ is called dual-adapted if $G$ is adapted. Equivalently, a rooted 3,4 -map $G^{*}$ is dual-adapted if the deletion of less than 4 edges does not disconnect $G^{*}$ into 2 subgraphs having more than 1 vertex each. Note that dual-adaptedness is less demanding than 4 -edge connectivity since vertices of degree 3 are allowed.

2.2. Grand-Schnyder structures. In this subsection we recall some definitions and results from [BFL24] about 4-GS labelings and 4-GS woods.

Let $G$ be a 3,4 -angulation of the square. A 4 -labeling of $G$ is an assignment of a label in $\{1,2,3,4\}$ to each inner corner of $G$; see for example Figure 10(a). A 4-GS labeling of $G$ is a 4 -labeling satisfying certain local conditions represented in Figure 9. These conditions are best expressed in terms of jumps. Consider a 4 -labeling of $G$. Let $c$ and $c^{\prime}$ be two inner corners of $G$, and let $i$ and $i^{\prime}$ be their respective labels. The label jump from the corner $c$ to the corner $c^{\prime}$ is defined as the integer $\delta$ in $\{0,1,2,3\}$ such that $i+\delta \equiv i^{\prime}$ modulo 4 (in other words, the label jump $\delta$ is $i^{\prime}-i$ if $i^{\prime}-i \geq 0$, and $i^{\prime}-i+4$ otherwise).

For an inner vertex $v$ of $G$, the sum of clockwise jumps around $v$ is the sum of label jumps between consecutive corners in clockwise order around $v$. Similarly, the sum of clockwise jumps around a face $f$ is the sum of label jumps between consecutive corners in clockwise order around $f$.

Definition 2.1. Let $G$ be a 3,4-angulation of the square. As usual, we assume that the outer vertices of $G$ are denoted by $v_{1}, \ldots, v_{4}$ in clockwise order around the outer face. A 4-GS labeling of $G$ is a 4-labeling satisfying the following conditions.
(L0) For all $i \in\{1,2,3,4\}$, all the inner corners incident to $v_{i}$ have label $i$.
(L1) For every inner vertex or face of $G$, the sum of clockwise jumps around this vertex or face is 4 .
(L2) The label jump from a corner to the next corner around a face are always strictly positive.
(L3) Let $e$ be an inner edge incident to a face $f$ of degree 3. Let $c$ and $c^{\prime}$ be the consecutive corners incident to $e$ in clockwise order around $f$, and let $v$ be the vertex incident to $c^{\prime}$. The label jump $\delta$ from $c$ to $c^{\prime}$ and the label jump $\epsilon$ from $c^{\prime}$ to the next corner in clockwise order around $v$ satisfy $\delta+\epsilon \geq 2$.

Let $G$ be an irreducible (i.e. adapted) triangulation of the square. Lemma 2.4. Let $G$ be a 3,4-angulation of the square endowed with a 4-GS labeling. Let $B_{o}, B_{e}, A_{o}, A_{e}, \widetilde{A}_{o}, \widetilde{A}_{e}$ be the oriented planar maps defined as above. Then $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ and $\widetilde{A}_{e}$ are bipolar orientations. Consequently, $A_{o}$ and $A_{e}$ are acyclic orientations, and $B_{o}, B_{e}$ are bipolar orientations.

Proof. We start by showing that $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ is acyclic. Suppose the contrary. For each simple directed cycle of $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ we consider the region of the plane it encloses. Let $C$ be a directed cycle of $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ whose enclosed region is minimal (not containing a smaller such region). By minimality of $C$, there is no directed path in $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ starting and ending on $C$ and staying strictly in the region enclosed by $C$. Since every inner vertex of $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ is incident to at least one incoming and at least one outgoing arc, the region enclosed by $C$ does not contain any arc (otherwise, one could extend this arc into a directed path in both direction, so as to construct a directed path starting and ending on $C$ and staying in the region enclosed by $C$ ). Hence the arcs of $C$ are all incident to a single inner face of $G$. However, it is easy to check that for any inner face $f$ of $G$, the set of arcs of $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ incident to $f$ does not form a directed cycle. Indeed any inner face $f$ of $G$ is incident to at least one arc of $A_{o}$ oriented clockwise around $f$ (since $f$ has a corner labeled 2 or a corner labeled 3 , or both) and to at least one arc of $A_{o}$ oriented counterclockwise around $f$ (since $f$ has a corner labeled 1 or a corner labeled 4 , or both). This gives a contradiction and proves that $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ is acyclic. Furthermore, we claim the the unique source (resp. sink) of $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ is the vertex resulting from the contraction of the outer edge $\left\{v_{1}, v_{2}\right\}$ (resp. $\left.\left\{v_{3}, v_{4}\right\}\right)$. Indeed any inner vertex of $G$ is incident to at least one incoming arc and one outgoing arc (since the inner arcs of $B_{o}=W_{1} \cup W_{3}^{-}$are in $A_{o}$ ), hence this also holds for any inner vertex of $\widetilde{A}_{o}$. Hence $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ is a bipolar orientation.

Since $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ is acyclic, the orientation $A_{o}$ is also acyclic (because if $A_{o}$ contained a directed cycle, then its contraction $\widetilde{A}_{o}$ would also contain one). In fact $A_{o} \cup\left\{\left(v_{2}, v_{1}\right),\left(v_{3}, v_{4}\right)\right\}$ is also acyclic (for the same reason). Hence the orientation $B_{o}$, which is contained in $A_{o} \cup\left\{\left(v_{2}, v_{1}\right),\left(v_{3}, v_{4}\right)\right\}$, is also acyclic. Furthermore $B_{o}$ is bipolar since its unique sink (resp. source) is the outer vertex $v_{2}$ (resp. $v_{4}$ ).

Similarly, $\widetilde{A}_{e}$ is bipolar, $A_{e}$ is acyclic, and $B_{e}$ is bipolar (all the definitions coincide with the odd case up to increasing the indices by 1 modulo 4 ).
2.4. Dual Grand-Schnyder structures. We now recall from [BFL24] some basic facts about dual 4-GS structures.

Let $G$ be a 3,4 -angulation of the square. Let $G^{*}$ be the rooted 3,4 -map dual to $G$, and let $v_{\infty}$ be its root vertex. (L1*) Around every non-root face or non-root vertex, the sum of clockwise jumps is 4.
(L2*) Consecutive corners around a vertex have distinct labels.
(L3*) Let a be an non-root arc whose initial vertex has degree 3. Let $c, c^{\prime}, c^{\prime \prime}$ be the left-initial, right initial and right terminal corners of $e$. It is clear from the definitions that the blue and orange trees $T_{b}$ and $T_{o}$ of $\mathcal{S}$ are equal to the trees $W_{1}$ and $W_{3}$ of $\mathcal{L}$. Hence every edge of $G$ belongs to the odd bipolar orientation $B_{o}=W_{1} \cup W_{3}^{-}$. Similarly, every edge of $G$ belongs to the even bipolar orientation $B_{e}=W_{4} \cup W_{2}^{-}$. Note also that, for any inner vertex $v$ and any $i \in\{1,2,3,4\}$, the path $P_{i}(v)$ defined from the separating decomposition $\mathcal{S}$ is equal to the path from $v$ to $v_{i}$ in the tree $W_{i}$. Therefore, the separating paths $P_{o}(v)$ and $P_{e}(v)$ defined from $\mathcal{S}$ are equal to the odd and even paths defined from $\mathcal{L}$, and the placement of vertices by the face-counting algorithm in [BH12] based on $\mathcal{S}$ coincides with the placement from the face-counting algorithm based on $\mathcal{L}$.

In conclusion, the straight-line drawing algorithm from Theorem 3.1 interpolates between the compact version of the algorithm from [Fus09], and the face-counting algorithm from [BH12].
Remark 3.2. It is shown in [BH12] that the face-counting algorithm can be supplemented by a compaction procedure that significantly reduces the grid-size. It is an open question to

determine how to best extend this compaction procedure to the more general setting of the present article.

Lemma 3.5. Let $G$ be a 3,4-angulation of the square endowed with a 4-GS labeling. Let $\vec{A}_{o}$ and $\vec{A}_{e}$ be the augmented bipolar contractions of $G$. The face-counting coordinates $\left(\ell_{e}(v), r_{o}(v)\right)$ defined in Section 3.1 are such that the function $\ell_{e}$ is $\vec{A}_{o}$-increasing and the function $r_{o}$ is $\vec{A}_{e^{-}}$ increasing.

This could also have been shown by the same arguments as in the proof of Lemma 2.4, upon observing that the contours of the new faces of degree 3 (created by the insertion of diagonals) are acyclic.

Proof of Lemma 3.5. Let us prove that the face-counting function $\ell_{e}$ is $\vec{A}_{o}$-increasing. There are three facts to prove:
(a) if $\{u, v\}$ is an edge in $\overrightarrow{A_{o}}$, then $\ell_{e}(u)=\ell_{e}(v)$,
(b) if $(u, v)$ is an arc in $A_{o}$, then $\ell_{e}(u)<\ell_{e}(v)$,
(c) if $(u, v)$ is a diagonal arc of $\vec{A}_{o}$, then $\ell_{e}(u)<\ell_{e}(v)$.

Recall that $\ell_{e}(v)$ is defined as the number of faces of the bipolar orientation $B_{e}$ on the left of the path $P_{e}(v)=P_{4}(v) \cup P_{2}(v)^{-}$.

We start by proving (a). The statement is clear for outer edges, so we now consider an inner edge $e=\{u, v\} \in \overrightarrow{A_{o}}$. Recall that the corners incident to $e$ are labeled as indicated in Figure 11(b), so we have $(u, v) \in W_{4}$ and $(v, u) \in W_{2}$. In this case the paths $P_{e}(u)$ and $P_{e}(v)$ are equal, hence $\ell_{e}(u)=\ell_{e}(v)$.

Next, we prove (b). The statement is clear for outer arcs, so we now consider an inner arc $a=(u, v)$ in $A_{o}$. The condition satisfied by the labels of the corners incident to the arc $a$ is indicated in Figure 11(b). Let us first suppose that left-init $(a)=1$. In this case left-term $(a) \in\{3,4\}$. We contend that the path $P_{e}(u)$ stays (weakly) to the left of $P_{e}(v)$. The situation is represented in Figure 21(a). Consider the path $P=P_{2}(u)^{-} \cup\{a\} \cup P_{4}(v)$. The label of the corners around $a$ implies that the first arc of $P_{4}(u)$ is strictly to the left of $P$ as indicated in Figure 21(a). Moreover, $P_{4}(u)$ cannot cross $P$. Indeed, $P_{4}(u)$ and $P_{2}(u)$ have no vertex in common except $u$ (otherwise there would be a directed cycle in the bipolar orientation $\left.B_{e}\right)$; and if $P_{4}(u)$ and $P_{4}(v)$ have a common vertex then they merge after that vertex. Hence $P_{4}(u)$ stays on the left of $P$. Thus $P_{e}(u)$ stays to the left of $P$. Similarly, $P_{2}(v)$ starts weakly to the right of $P$, hence it stays weakly to the right of $P$. Thus $P_{e}(v)$ stays to the right of $P$. In conclusion $P_{e}(u)$ is to the left of $P$ which is to the left of $P_{e}(v)$. This gives the desired inequality $\ell_{e}(u) \leq \ell_{e}(v)$ for the number of faces on the left of $P_{e}(u)$ and $P_{e}(v)$. The inequality is actually strict since $P_{e}(u) \neq P$. This completes the proof for the case left-init $(a)=1$.

A similar proof can be given in the cases right-init $(a)=2$, or left-term $(a)=3$, or right-term $(a)=$ 4 which are represented in Figure 21(b). Indeed in all these cases the label condition implies that

$a$ is on the right of $P_{e}(u)$ and on the left of $P_{e}(v)$, which is enough to prove that $\ell_{e}(u)<\ell_{e}(v)$ by reasoning as above.

Lastly we prove (c). There are two types of diagonal arcs, as represented in Figure 21(c). In both cases, the diagonal $a=(u, v)$ is to the right of $P_{e}(u)$ and to the left of $P_{e}(v)$. Hence, as before we can see that the path $P=P_{2}(u)^{-} \cup\{a\} \cup P_{4}(v)$ is at the right of $P_{e}(u)$ and at the left of $P_{e}(v)$, which implies $\ell_{e}(u)<\ell_{e}(v)$ as desired. This completes the proof that the function $\ell_{e}$ is $\vec{A}_{o}$-increasing.

The proof that the function $r_{o}$ is $\vec{A}_{e}$-increasing is almost identical and left to the reader.

3.3. Proof of planarity. In this subsection we prove Theorem 3.3. We will rely on a general planarity criterion that we now state. It is well-known and appears in different forms in the literature, for instance as Lemma 4.4 in [dV03], with references. We provide a short proof for completeness.

Let $G$ be a 2-connected planar map (for instance, an adapted 3,4 -angulation of the square). Note that the contour of every face of $G$ is a simple cycle. A piecewise-linear drawing of a graph $G$ is a drawing of $G$ in the plane where every edge is represented as a (non-empty) selfavoiding concatenation of segments. The drawing is called valid for a face $f$ of $G$ if the curve corresponding to the clockwise contour ${ }^{3}$ of $f$ is a polygonal simple curve in the plane whose interior is on its right.

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{3}$ Clockwise means that the contour is traversed with $f$ on its right if $f$ is an inner face, and with $f$ on its left if $f$ is the outer face.

Lemma 3.7. Let $G$ be a 2-connected planar map. Consider a piecewise-linear drawing of the graph underlying $G$. If the drawing is valid for every face of $G$ (including the outer face), then the drawing is planar (and corresponds to the planar map $G$ ).

Proof. Consider a piecewise-linear drawing of a 2 -connected planar map $G$, which is valid for every face. Let $F$ be the set of faces of $G$. For a face $f \in F$, let $P_{f}$ be the polygon representing $f$ in the drawing, and let $\Sigma_{f}$ be the set of points corresponding to the vertices incident to $f$. If $f$ is an inner face (resp. is the outer face), we define $N_{f}: \mathbb{R}^{2}\left\langle\Sigma_{f} \rightarrow\left\{0, \frac{1}{2}, 1\right\}\right.$ to be the indicator function for $f$, assigning value 1 to the points in the interior (resp. exterior) of $P_{f}$, value $1 / 2$ to the points on the boundary of $P_{f}$ (excluding $\Sigma_{f}$ ), and value 0 to the points in the exterior (resp. interior) of $P_{f}$. Let $\Sigma$ be the set of points in the plane that are images of vertices of $G$, and let $N$ be the function on $\mathbb{R}^{2}\left\langle\Sigma\right.$ defined as $N:=\sum_{f \in F} N_{f}$. As the drawing is valid for every face, the function $N$ is locally constant, hence it is constant. Since it is equal to 1 for a point in the drawing of the outer face far enough so that it avoids the polygons representing inner faces, it is constant equal to 1 . Moreover, at each vertex $v$, the fact that the drawing is valid for all faces ensures that the set of faces in clockwise order around $v$ forms a fan that wraps $k$ times (i.e., of total angle $2 k \pi$ ), for a positive integer $k$. Since $N=1$ in the neighborhood of $v$, we must have $k=1$. Similarly, no two vertices can be at the same point, nor a vertex intersect an edge, nor two edges intersect each other (any of these situations would imply that $N \geq 2$ in a neighborhood). This proves the planarity of the drawing.

In Section 4 we will also need the following complementary lemma:
Lemma 3.8. Let $G$ be a 2-connected planar map, endowed with a piecewise-linear drawing. Let $C=(C(t))_{t \in[0,1]}$ be the directed closed curve given by the drawing of the outer face contour of $G$ traversed clockwise. A point $p=C(t)$ is called outer-right-visible if there is a ray starting from $p$ to the right side of $C$ (locally at $p$ ) and reaching to infinity without meeting $C$ again. If the drawing is valid for every inner face of $G$, then there is no outer-right-visible point.

Proof. Assume the drawing is valid at every inner face, and consider a ray $\gamma$ starting on the right side of $C$ at a point $p=C(t)$ and reaching to infinity. Let $p^{\prime}$ be the farthest point on $\gamma$ that belongs to the drawing of an edge or vertex. Clearly, after leaving $p^{\prime}$ the ray $\gamma$ cannot visit any point on an edge or vertex, nor in an area corresponding to the drawing of an inner face. Hence, $p^{\prime}$ cannot be the image of a point on an inner edge, nor the image of an inner vertex $v$ (for this we need the validity for inner faces, which ensures that the inner faces incident to $v$ form a fan that wraps $k$ times around $v$ in the drawing, for some positive integer $k$ ). Hence $p^{\prime} \in C$. It only remains to show that $p^{\prime} \neq p$. If $p$ belongs to the drawing of an edge of $C$, then this edge is on the contour of an inner face $f$ whose drawing is valid, hence $\gamma$ starts within the interior of $f$ and will meet the contour of $f$ again, thus $p^{\prime} \neq p$. Suppose now that $p$ corresponds to the drawing of a vertex $v$ of $C$. In this case, the drawing of the inner faces incident to $v$ (which are all valid) form a fan that covers the right side of $C$ at $p$ (and possibly wraps around $p$ several more times). Hence $\gamma$ starts in the interior of an inner face, or in the drawing of an inner edge. In every case we conclude that $p^{\prime} \neq p$ which completes the proof.

Remark 3.9. The condition that the drawing is valid at every inner face is not enough to avoid self-intersections of the outer contour, as illustrated in Figure 22, where it can be seen that the drawing has no outer-right-visible point.

A vertex placement $\alpha$ induces a straight-line drawing of $G$ (in which each edge is represented by a segment). 3.4. Time complexity of the increasing function drawing algorithm. In this subsection we discuss the time complexity of the increasing function drawing algorithm presented in Section 3.2. We say that an algorithm for 3,4 -angulations can be performed in linear time if it can

be done in a number of arithmetic operations which is linear in the number of vertices. Note that the numbers of edges and faces of a 3,4 -angulation are linear in the number of vertices by the Euler relation combined with the face-edge incidence relation.

Let $G=(V, E)$ be an adapted 3,4 -angulation of the square. We aim to draw $G$ with vertices placed at integer coordinates. Using the increasing function drawing algorithm for this task amounts to:
(i) computing a 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}$, and the corresponding augmented bipolar contractions $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}, \overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{e}$, and
(ii) computing some integer-valued $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$-increasing and $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{e}$-increasing functions $h_{o}$ and $h_{e}$. For step (ii) we aim for a small grid size, so we want the increasing function $h_{o}, h_{e}$ to be tight. Precisely, an $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$-increasing function $h_{o}$ is called tight if it takes non-negative integer values and minimizes $\max \left(h_{o}\right)$ among such functions. Tightness for $h_{e}$ is defined similarly.

Step (i) can be completed in linear time. Indeed, a linear time algorithm for finding a 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}$ was given in [BFL24]. Moreover it is easy to see that computing the orientations $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}, \overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{e}$ from $\mathcal{L}$ can be done in linear time.

We now show that Step (ii) can also be completed in linear time. Given an acyclic directed graph $D$, we call source-level of a vertex $v$ of $D$ the maximal length of the directed paths ending at $v$ (so that the sources of $D$ are at source-level 0 ). As we now explain, the source-level of every vertex in a digraph $D=\left(V_{D}, E_{D}\right)$ can be computed in time linear in $\left|V_{D}\right|+\left|E_{D}\right|$. Recall that the topological ordering algorithm on $D$ returns a total order $\mathcal{O}$ of the vertex set $V_{D}$ such that every arc of $D$ is oriented from the smaller vertex to the greater vertex for the order $\mathcal{O}$. It is known that the topological ordering algorithm is linear in $\left|V_{D}\right|+\left|E_{D}\right|$. Once the total order $\mathcal{O}$ is fixed, one can compute the source-level of every vertex, by treating vertices in the order given by the total order $\mathcal{O}$ (from smallest to greatest): for every vertex $v$ the source-level of $v$ is 0 if $v$ is a source and

$$
\operatorname{source}-\operatorname{level}(v)=\max \left\{\operatorname{source}-\operatorname{level}(u)+1 \mid(u, v) \in E_{D}\right\}
$$

otherwise. This computation is also clearly linear in $\left|V_{D}\right|+\left|E_{D}\right|$.

Consider now the function $h_{o}: V \rightarrow \mathbb{N}$ defined by setting $h_{o}(v)$ to be the source-level of the vertex corresponding to $v$ in $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$ for all $v \in V$. It is easy to see that $h_{o}(v)$ is $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$-increasing (recall that $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$-increasing functions can be identified with functions on the vertex set of $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$ which are increasing along the arcs of $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$ ). Moreover, the increasing function $h_{o}$ is tight. Indeed, any $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$-increasing function $f: V \rightarrow \mathbb{N}$ satisfies

$$
\forall v \in V, h_{o}(v) \leq f(v)
$$

This property is easily shown by induction on the source-level of $v$ (or rather the source-level of the vertex corresponding to $v$ in $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$ ). Indeed we can identify $h_{o}$ and $f$ with some functions $h_{o}^{\prime}$ and $f^{\prime}$ on the vertex set $V^{\prime}$ of $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$, and we want to show $h_{o}^{\prime}(v) \leq f^{\prime}(v)$ for all $v \in V^{\prime}$. For the source $v_{0}$ of $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$, one has $h_{o}^{\prime}\left(v_{0}\right)=0 \leq f^{\prime}\left(v_{0}\right)$. And for any vertex $v \in V^{\prime}$ at source-level $k>0$, there is an arc $(u, v)$ of $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$ such that $u$ is at source-level $k-1$, hence the induction hypothesis gives $h_{o}^{\prime}(v)=h_{o}^{\prime}(u)+1 \leq f^{\prime}(u)+1 \leq f^{\prime}(v)$, which completes the proof. Hence $h_{o}$ is a tight $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{o}$-increasing function which can be computed in linear time.

Similarly the function $h_{e}(v): V \rightarrow \mathbb{N}$ defined by setting $h_{e}(v)$ to be the source-level of the vertex corresponding to $v$ in $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{e}$ is a tight $\overrightarrow{\mathcal{A}}_{e}$-increasing function which can be computed in linear time. We summarize our findings as follows:

Proposition 3.11. The increasing function algorithm for drawing an adapted 3,4-angulation of the square can be completed in linear time in the number of vertices.

3.5. Bounds on the grid size. In this subsection we discuss the size of the grid needed for our straight-line grid-drawing algorithms.

Let $G$ be an adapted 3,4-angulation of the square, and let $\mathcal{L}$ be a 4-GS labeling. Let $h_{o}, h_{e}$ be the tight increasing functions computed by the increasing-function algorithm. By definition the grid required for the vertex placement has size $m_{o} \times m_{e}$, where $m_{o}=\max \left(h_{o}\right)$ and $m_{e}=\max \left(h_{e}\right)$. We want to give some upper bounds on $m_{o}$ and $m_{e}$.

Since the face-counting algorithm presented in Section 3.1 produces some increasing functions $\ell_{e}$ and $r_{o}$, we get the following upper bounds for the dimension of the grid: $m_{o} \leq \max \left(\ell_{e}\right)$ and $m_{e} \leq \max \left(r_{o}\right)$. By definition, $\max \left(r_{o}\right)$ is the number of inner faces in the bipolar orientation $B_{o}$. Using the Euler relation, one gets $\max \left(r_{o}\right)=\mathbf{e}_{o}-\mathbf{v}+1$, where $\mathbf{v}$ is the number of inner vertices of $G$, and $\mathbf{e}_{o}$ is the number of inner edges in $B_{o}=W_{1} \cup W_{3}{ }^{-}$. Next, we observe that $\mathbf{e}_{o}=2 \mathbf{v}-\mathbf{d}_{o}$, where $\mathbf{d}_{o}$ is the number of inner edges of $G$ carrying both an arc in $W_{1}$ and an arc in $W_{3}$. Thus $\max \left(r_{o}\right)=\mathbf{v}+1-\mathbf{d}_{o}$. Similarly $\max \left(\ell_{e}\right)=\mathbf{v}+1-\mathbf{d}_{e}$ where $\mathbf{d}_{e}$ is the number of inner edges of $G$ carrying both an arc in $W_{2}$ and an arc in $W_{4}$. We summarize:

Proposition 3.12. Let $G$ be an adapted 3,4-angulation of the square, and let $\mathcal{L}$ be a 4-GS labeling. The increasing function algorithm provides a grid drawing of $G$ on a grid of size $m_{o} \times m_{e}$, with $m_{o} \leq \boldsymbol{v}+1-\boldsymbol{d}_{e}$ and $m_{e} \leq \boldsymbol{v}+1-\boldsymbol{d}_{o}$, where $\boldsymbol{d}_{o}$ (resp. $\boldsymbol{d}_{e}$ ) is the number of inner edges of $G$ carrying both an arc in $W_{1}$ and an arc in $W_{3}$ (resp. an arc in $W_{2}$ and an arc in $\left.W_{4}\right)$.

In the case where $G$ is a triangulation of the square, $\mathbf{d}_{e}+\mathbf{d}_{o}$ is the number $\mathbf{e}_{2}$ of inner edges having 2 colors in the 4-GS woods (because each arc has at most one color for any 4-GS structure on any triangulation of the square). Let $\mathbf{e}_{0}, \mathbf{e}_{1}, \mathbf{e}_{2}$ be the number of inner edges having $0,1,2$ colors respectively, and let $\mathbf{e}=\mathbf{e}_{0}+\mathbf{e}_{1}+\mathbf{e}_{2}$ be the total number of inner edges. The Euler relation (combined with the incidence relation between faces and edges) gives $\mathbf{e}=3 \mathbf{v}+1$, and the fact that each inner vertex is incident to one outgoing arc of each color gives $\mathbf{e}_{1}+2 \mathbf{e}_{2}=4 \mathbf{v}$. This implies $\mathbf{e}_{2}=\mathbf{v}-1+\mathbf{e}_{o}$, and $m_{o}+m_{e}=2 \mathbf{v}+2-\mathbf{e}_{2}=\mathbf{v}+3-\mathbf{e}_{0} \leq \mathbf{v}+3$. Thus, for a triangulation of the square, the half-perimeter of the grid drawing is strictly less than the number of vertices.
3.6. Reduction of the grid size. In this subsection we discuss some optimizations of the increasing function drawing algorithm aimed at reducing the grid size. These improvements will be obtained by relaxing some requirements related to diagonal arcs for the increasing functions $h_{o}, h_{e}$.

In order to state which requirements can be relaxed, we first need to classify the diagonal $\operatorname{arcs}$ of $\vec{A}_{o}$ and $\vec{A}_{e}$. We refer to Figure 19 for the definition of the diagonal arcs. For a diagonal $\operatorname{arc} a$ of $A_{o}$ or $A_{e}$, we denote by $f(a)$ the inner face of $G$ containing $a$. Each of the 4 edges of $G$ incident to the face $f(a)$ can be either missing if they are in $\overrightarrow{A_{o}} \cup \overrightarrow{A_{e}}$, or converging if they are oriented the same way in $A_{o}$ and $A_{e}$, or diverging if they are oriented in opposite directions in $A_{o}$ and $A_{e}$. We let missing $(a)$, converging $(a)$ and diverging $(a)$ be the number of missing, converging and diverging edges incident to $f(a)$. Note that missing $(a) \in\{0,1,2\}$ and missing $(a)+$ converging $(a)+$ diverging $(a)=4$.

We call all the diagonal arcs of $\vec{A}_{o}$ and $\vec{A}_{e}$ weak, except for the diagonal arcs $a$ of $\vec{A}_{e}$ such that converging $(a)=4$ or diverging $(a)=4$ which are called strict. We call a diagonal arc $a$ mandatory unless $|\operatorname{converging}(a)-\operatorname{diverging}(a)|=\operatorname{missing}(a)$. It is easy to check that a diagonal $\operatorname{arc} a$ is non-mandatory if and only if it satisfies one of the following conditions:
(i) missing $(a)=0$ and converging $(a)=2$,
(ii) missing $(a)=1$ and converging $(a) \in\{1,2\}$,
(iii) missing $(a)=2$.

Indeed, when $\operatorname{missing}(a)=0$ the condition $\mid \operatorname{converging}(a)-\operatorname{diverging}(a) \mid=0$ is equivalent to converging $(a)=2$, (since converging $(a)+$ diverging $(a)=4)$, while when missing $(a)=2$ one can check that converging $(a) \in\{0,2\}$ (see Figure 19 and observe that the missing edges are either both in $\overrightarrow{A_{o}}$ or both in $\overrightarrow{A_{e}}$ ) hence $\mid \operatorname{converging}(a)-\operatorname{diverging}(a) \mid=2$ (since converging $(a)+$ diverging $(a)=2)$.

Note that a strict diagonal arc is always mandatory.

For the diagonal $\operatorname{arc} a \in \vec{A}_{o}$ on the left of Figure 20(c) one has missing $(a)=0$, converging $(a)=1$, and diverging $(a)=3$, hence this arc is weak and mandatory. For the diagonal $\operatorname{arc} b \in \vec{A}_{e}$ on the right of Figure 20(c) one has missing $(b)=2$, converging $(a)=0$, and diverging $(a)=2$, hence this arc is weak and non-mandatory.

We say that a function $g: V \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is quasi $\vec{A}_{o}$-increasing (resp. quasi $\vec{A}_{e}$-increasing) if it satisfies the following 3 conditions:

- $g(u)=g(v)$ for every edge $\{u, v\}$ in $\overrightarrow{A_{o}}$ (resp. $\overrightarrow{A_{e}}$ ),
- $g(u) \leq g(v)$ for every weak mandatory diagonal $\operatorname{arc}(u, v)$ in $\vec{A}_{o}$ (resp. $\vec{A}_{e}$ ),
- $g(u)<g(v)$ for every $\operatorname{arc}(u, v)$ in $A_{o}$ (resp. $A_{e}$ ) and every strict mandatory diagonal $\operatorname{arc}(u, v)$ in $\vec{A}_{o}$ (resp. $\vec{A}_{e}$ ).
Clearly any $\vec{A}_{o}$-increasing function is quasi $\vec{A}_{o}$-increasing (and similarly for $\vec{A}_{e}$ ). We can now state a slightly stronger version of Theorem 3.3.

Theorem 3.14. Let $G$ be an adapted 3,4-angulation of the square, let $\mathcal{L}$ be a 4-GS labeling, and let $\vec{A}_{o}$ and $\vec{A}_{e}$ be the corresponding augmented bipolar contractions of $G$. Let $h_{o}$ be a quasi $\vec{A}_{o}$-increasing function and $h_{e}$ be a quasi $\vec{A}_{e}$-increasing function. Placing each vertex $v$ of $G$ at coordinates $\left(h_{o}(v), h_{e}(v)\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{2}$ gives a planar straight-line drawing of $G$.

otherwise.

# 4. Orthogonal drawing of planar maps with Vertex-degree at most 4 

In this section we turn our attention to the dual picture: we will define orthogonal drawing algorithms for dual-adapted rooted 3,4-maps, which are the maps dual to the adapted 3,4angulations of the square.

Recall that a planar orthogonal drawing of a graph is a planar drawing where each edge is represented as a sequence of horizontal and vertical line segments. For convenience (and in view of displaying drawings with at most one bend per edge), we adopt the convention of not drawing the root-vertex $v_{\infty}$, as in [BF12, FKV14].
Definition 4.1. Let $G^{*}$ be a rooted 3,4-map, let $v_{\infty}$ be its root vertex, and let $e_{1}^{*}, \ldots, e_{4}^{*}$ be the root edges. A suspended planar orthogonal drawing for $G^{*}$, or SPO drawing for short, is a planar orthogonal drawing of the map obtained from $G^{*}$ by disconnecting the edges $e_{1}^{*}, \ldots, e_{4}^{*}$ from $v_{\infty}$, in which the edges $e_{1}^{*}, \ldots, e_{4}^{*}$ are drawn as dangling arrows in the outer face whose directions are west, north, east and south respectively ${ }^{4}$.

For instance, the drawing of Figure 26(b) is an SPO drawing.
The algorithms we present in this section are based on dual 4-GS structures, which were introduced in [BFL24]. We first define a "face-counting" SPO drawing algorithm which generalizes Bernardi and Fusy's algorithm [BF12], and then a more general (and more compact) "increasing functions" SPO drawing algorithm, which also generalizes He's algorithm [He93].

- if $a$ is an arc having $f$ on its right with labels (right-init $(a)$, right-term $(a))=(1,2)$, then it is drawn down,
- if $a$ is an arc having $f$ on its right with labels (right-init $(a)$, right-term $(a))=(2,3)$, then it is drawn left,
- if $a$ is an arc having $f$ on its right with labels (right-init $(a)$, right-term $(a))=(3,4)$, then it is drawn up.
Finally, an arc $a$ having $f$ on its right with labels (right-init $(a)$, right-term $(a))=(4,2)$ will be drawn as a bent edge going "right then down". This is represented in Figure 34(c). Symmetric results olds for an arc with label (right-init $(a)$, right-term $(a))=(1,3)$ or $(2,4)$ or $(3,1)$.

To summarize, every non-root edged of $G^{*}$ can be drawn following the $\mathcal{L}^{*}$-rule which produces an orthogonal drawing of $G^{\prime}$. Moreover, for each inner face $f$, the drawing of the clockwise contour of $f$ is as follows: the 1 -run drawn going down-right, a down segment, the 2 -run drawn left-down, a left segment, the 3 -run drawn up-left, an up segment, the 4 -run going right-up, a right segment.

It is clear from the properties stated above that consecutive runs of $f$ (that is, a $i$-run and a $(i+1)$-run) cannot intersect one another. Hence the drawing is valid for the face $f$ unless opposite runs (that is, a $i$-run and a $(i+2)$-run) intersect each other. Now, the function $h_{o}^{*}$ is increasing along odd diagonal arcs inside $f$ (which goes from the end of the 4 -run to the end of the 2 -run), hence the 4 -run is strictly to the left of the 2 -run; and the function $h_{e}^{*}$ is increasing along even diagonal arcs inside $f$ (which goes from the end of the 3 -run to the end of the 1 -run), hence the 3 -run is strictly below the 1 -run. In conclusion, the drawing of $f$ is as illustrated in Figure 33, and it is valid.

In order to finish the proof of Theorem 4.6, we need to show that the orthogonal drawing of $G^{\prime}$ is valid for the outer face.

Consider the vertices on the outer boundary of $G^{\prime}$ that are adjacent to the root vertex $v_{\infty}$ in $G^{*}$. Let us denote the vertex incident to the root-edge $e_{1}^{*}$ (resp. $e_{2}^{*}, e_{3}^{*}, e_{4}^{*}$ ) by $v_{1}^{*}$ (resp. $v_{2}^{*}$, $\left.v_{3}^{*}, v_{4}^{*}\right)$. The vertices $v_{1}^{*}, v_{2}^{*}, v_{3}^{*}, v_{4}^{*}$ divide the clockwise outer contour of $G^{\prime}$ into four parts. We refer to the part from $v_{i}^{*}$ to $v_{i+1}^{*}$ as the outer $(i+1)$-run, as all the labels on the outer face of this part are $(i+1)$. Some of the outer runs can be empty since we could have $v_{i}^{*}=v_{i+1}^{*}$; however we cannot have $v_{i}^{*}=v_{i+2}^{*}$ unless $G^{\prime}$ consists of a single vertex.

It is not hard to see that, for any pair of increasing functions $h_{o}^{*}$ and $h_{e}^{*}$, the four runs of the outer contour satisfy some specific inequalities about $h_{o}^{*}$ and $h_{e}^{*}$, which translate into the following orientation properties:

- The outer 2-run is directed up-right.
- The outer 3 -run is directed right-down.
- The outer 4 -run is directed down-left.
- The outer 1 -run is directed left-up.

In other words, the shapes of the four outer runs are similar to the shapes of the four runs of a generic inner face (with index of the run offset by 2). See Figure 35(a) (left) for an example. This alone however does not guarantee that the drawing of the outer face of $G^{\prime}$ is valid. The difference is that in the case of inner faces, the condition on diagonal arcs ensure that opposite runs do not intersect. For the outer face however, not only are such diagonal arc requirements non-existent, but also the outer contour may have cut vertices in the first place.

Fortunately, the shapes of the four runs imply that all cut vertices, if they exist, must belong to one of the two pairs of opposite outer runs, say the outer 3 -run and the outer 1 -run. The cut vertices divide $G^{\prime}$ into a chain of 2 -connected subgraphs, that we call 2-blocks of $G$ (consecutive 2-blocks intersect at a cut vertex). It is clear from the orientation property of the outer-face of $G^{\prime}$ that the drawing of $G^{\prime}$ is planar if and only if the drawing of each 2-block is planar. An example is illustrated in Figure 35(a) (right).

Let $H$ be a 2 -block of $G$. Recall that the drawing of each inner face of $H$ is valid by Lemma 4.10. Hence, if we can show that the drawing of the outer face of $H$ is valid, then we can invoke Lemma 3.7 to conclude that the drawing of $H$ is planar. Let us suppose for contradiction that the drawing of the outer face of $H$ is not valid. Given the orientation property of the runs, this implies that the boundary of $H$ must have some outer-right-visible point (recall the definition from Lemma 3.8 in Section 3.3). This is impossible according to Lemma 3.8. Therefore the outer face of $H$ is valid, and by Lemma 3.7, the drawing of $H$ is planar.

Since the drawing of every 2-block of $G$ is planar, the drawing of the whole graph $G^{\prime}$ is planar. It is also clear that the placements of $v_{i}^{*}$ 's are extremal in their respective directions, and hence the four dangling arrows can be added to the outer face, completing a valid SPO drawing of $G^{*}$. This completes the proof of Theorem 4.6.
4.4. Comparison to He's algorithm. We now compare the increasing function algorithm of Theorem 4.6 to He's algorithm from [He93]. He's algorithm is based on a transversal structure on an irreducible triangulation $G$ and a pair of increasing functions on the faces of the red and blue submaps $G_{r}$ and $G_{b}$. As explained in Section 2.2, each transversal structure also corresponds to a 4-GS labeling, and Remark 4.9 points out that $G_{r}$ and $G_{b}$ are equal to the augmented bipolar orientations $B_{e}^{\prime}$ and $B_{o}^{\prime}$. Given the duality relations between the dual bipolar contractions $\widetilde{A}_{o}^{*}, \widetilde{A}_{e}^{*}$ and $B_{o}^{\prime}, B_{o}^{\prime}$, it is easy to see that the increasing functions on the faces of $G_{r}$ and $G_{b}$, which are used in He's algorithm, naturally corresponds to a pair of increasing functions on the vertices of $\widetilde{A}_{o}^{*}$ and $\widetilde{A}_{e}^{*}$. We claim that such functions are also increasing functions on $\overrightarrow{\widetilde{A}}_{o}^{*}$ and $\overrightarrow{\widetilde{A}}_{e}^{*}$, because they automatically increase along the diagonal arcs. To see this, we can investigate the shape of faces in the drawing. First, note that an edge connecting two vertices of degree 3 cannot have exactly two colors with different parity, and hence every edge of $G^{*}$ is drawn with no bend. Next, inside each inner face of $G^{*}$, all four labels must appear, and with an analysis as in Section 4.3, one can observe that the shape of the four runs around an inner face of $G^{*}$ degenerates to something simple. Namely,

- the 1-run is drawn as a sequence of edges directed horizontally to the right,
- the 2 -run is drawn as a sequence of edges directed vertically downward,
- the 3 -run is drawn as a sequence of edges directed horizontally to the left,
- the 4 -run is drawn as a sequence of edges directed vertically upward.

Consequently, each inner face $f$ of $G^{*}$ is drawn as a rectangle, with the four corners of that rectangle corresponding to the last vertices incident to a corner of label 1,2,3,4 respectively in clockwise order around $f$. See Figure 35(b) for an illustration. Hence the functions used in He's algorithm already ensures strict increments along diagonal arcs. In short, the algorithm of [He93] is the same as the increasing function algorithm from Theorem 4.6 restricted to the case where all non-rooted vertices have degree 3 .
4.5. Properties of the SPO drawings. In this subsection we discuss some additional properties of the SPO drawings obtained by the increasing function algorithm. In previous subsections, we have investigated the shapes of the embedded faces, and we also remarked that an edge connecting two degree 3 vertices must be straight. Here we investigate some further orientation properties of embedded edges. These properties will provide some intuitions for the bend-minimization method discussed in Section 5.3.

There is a particular type of edges we are interested in. We say that a non-root arc $a=(u, v)$ is special if we have

$$
(\text { right-init }(a), \text { right-term }(a), \text { left-term }(a), \text { left-init }(a))=(k, k, k+2, k+3)
$$

for some $k \in\{1,2,3,4\}$. If one arc of an edge $e$ is special, then we also call $e$ special. See Figure 36(a) for an example.

Special edges satisfy some unusual properties. For one thing, from Condition (L3*) of the definition of dual 4-GS labelings, one can easily see that if an arc $a=(u, v)$ is special, then $u$ must be a vertex of degree 4 and $v$ of degree 3 . Furthermore, using the terminology of $i$-runs introduced in Subsection 4.3, one can easily verify that each run around a face contains at most one special edge, and if there is one then it has to be the last edge on that run (in clockwise order).

We now state the orientation properties of edges in our drawings.

- An arc whose initial vertex has degree 3 never turns left: it is either drawn as a straight segment, or it turns right.
- An arc with a unique color $k$ is drawn so that it starts by going in direction $k$.
- An arc with colors $k$ and $k+1$ is drawn so that it starts by going in direction $k$, unless it is part of a special edge, in which case it starts by going in direction $k+1$.

Now suppose an arc $a=(u, v)$ has a unique color $k$, and $u$ has degree 3 . For it to turn left, the opposite $\operatorname{arc}-a$ needs to have a unique color $k+1$, but this violates Condition (L3*) of dual 4-GS labelings.

4.6. On allowing vertices of degree 2. In this subsection we explain how to draw graphs having some vertices of degree 2 .

For an arbitrary graph with a vertex $v$ of degree 2 , we call erasing $v$ the operation of deleting $v$ and replacing the 2 incident edges $\left\{v, u_{1}\right\}$ and $\left\{v, u_{2}\right\}$ by a single edge $\left\{u_{1}, u_{2}\right\}$. See figure 37(a).
