Figure 37. (a) Erasing a vertex of degree 2. (b) Two possible embeddings of a chain with five vertices of degree 2 .

Now, let $G^{\circ}$ be a planar map whose vertex degrees are in $\{2,3,4\}$, with a designated root vertex $v_{\infty}$. For simplicity let us suppose $v_{\infty}$ is not incident to any vertex of degree 2 . Let $G^{*}$ be the planar map obtained by erasing all the vertices of degree 2 . Then every non-root edge of $G^{*}$ corresponds to a path of edges in $G^{\circ}$.

Assuming that $G^{*}$ is a dual-adapted rooted 3,4-map, we claim that we can easily obtain a grid SPO drawing for $G^{\circ}$. This takes two steps:
(1) Compute a dual 4-GS labeling on $G^{*}$, and run the increasing function algorithm with an additional requirement: if a non-root edge $e$ of $G^{*}$ corresponds to a path in $G^{\circ}$ with $N_{e}$ edges, then $e$ needs to be drawn with total length at least $N_{e}$ (either as a straight segment or as a bent-edge).
(2) Insert the vertices of degree 2 on the edges of $G^{*}$ they belong to. Due to the additional requirement in Step (1), they all can be placed at grid points.
The additional requirement in Step (1) is easy to achieve: for each edge $e$ of $G^{*}$, record the length $N_{e}$ of the corresponding path in $G^{\circ}$. Then, when computing the increasing functions, make sure that the increments along $e$ in $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$ and $\vec{A}_{e}^{*}$ sum to at least $N_{e}$. This ensures that the total length of $e$ in the drawing is at least $N_{e}$. See Figure 37(b) for an illustration.
4.7. Time complexity. In this subsection we discuss the time complexity and the grid size that can be achieved by the increasing function orthogonal drawing algorithm.

Let $G^{*}$ be a dual-adapted rooted 3,4-map. To perform the increasing function orthogonal drawing algorithm one needs to:
(i) compute a dual 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}^{*}$, and the corresponding orientations $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}, \vec{A}_{e}^{*}$, and
(ii) compute some integer-valued $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$-increasing and $\vec{A}_{e}^{*}$-increasing functions $h_{o}^{*}$ and $h_{e}^{*}$ that are tight (recall the definition from Section 3.4).
Step (i) can be completed in linear time since it was proved in [BFL24] that 4-GS labeling could be completed in linear time. Step (ii) can be completed using a similar procedure as in the primal case, which is elaborated in Section 3.4. We summarize these claims into the following statement.

Proposition 4.12. The increasing function orthogonal drawing algorithm for drawing a dualadapted rooted 3,4-map can be completed in linear time in the number of vertices.

We mention that the time complexity remains linear when allowing for vertices of degree 2 using the method discussed in Section 4.6.
4.8. Bound on the grid size. In this subsection we discuss the size of the grid needed for the orthogonal grid-drawing algorithms.

Let $G^{*}$ be a dual-adapted rooted 3,4-map, and let $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ be a dual 4-GS labeling. Denote by $m_{o}^{*} \times m_{e}^{*}$ the grid size resulting from the tight increasing functions associated to $\mathcal{L}^{*}$. Note that $m_{o}^{*}$ is the maximal length of directed paths in $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$, and $m_{e}^{*}$ is the maximal length of directed paths in $\vec{A}_{e}^{*}$. In general, it seems difficult to estimate $m_{o}^{*}$ and $m_{e}^{*}$. However, an obvious bound is $m_{o}^{*} \leq \mathbf{v}\left(\vec{A}_{o}^{*}\right)-1$, where $\mathbf{v}\left(\vec{A}_{o}^{*}\right)$ is the number of vertices of $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$, and similarly $m_{e}^{*} \leq \mathbf{v}\left(\vec{A}_{e}^{*}\right)-1$, where $\mathbf{v}\left(\vec{A}_{e}^{*}\right)$ is the number of vertices of $\vec{A}_{e}^{*}$.

Now, recall from Section 4.2 the duality relations between $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$ and $B_{e}^{\prime}=B_{e} \cup U_{e}$, and between $\left(\vec{A}_{e}^{*}\right)^{-}$and $B_{o}^{\prime}=B_{o} \cup U_{o}$ (see Remark 4.9). This implies $m_{o}^{*} \leq \mathbf{f}\left(B_{e}^{\prime}\right)-1$ and $m_{e}^{*} \leq \mathbf{f}\left(B_{o}^{\prime}\right)-1$, where $\mathbf{f}\left(B_{e}^{\prime}\right)$ and $\mathbf{f}\left(B_{o}^{\prime}\right)$ are the number of inner faces of $B_{e}^{\prime}$ and $B_{o}^{\prime}$. Since $B_{e}^{\prime}=B_{e} \cup U_{e}$ and $B_{o}^{\prime}=B_{o} \cup U_{o}$ we get

$$
\mathbf{f}\left(B_{e}^{\prime}\right)=\mathbf{f}\left(B_{e}\right)+\left|U_{e}\right| \text { and } \mathbf{f}\left(B_{o}^{\prime}\right)=\mathbf{f}\left(B_{e}\right)+\left|U_{o}\right|
$$

where $\mathbf{f}\left(B_{e}\right)$ is the number of inner faces of $B_{e}$, and $\mathbf{f}\left(B_{o}\right)$ is the number of inner faces of $B_{o}$.
It was shown in Section 3.5 that $\mathbf{f}\left(B_{e}\right)=\mathbf{v}+1-\mathbf{d}_{e}$, and $\mathbf{f}\left(B_{o}\right)=\mathbf{v}+1-\mathbf{d}_{o}$, where $\mathbf{v}$ is the number of inner vertices of the primal map $G$, and $\mathbf{d}_{e}$ (resp. $\mathbf{d}_{o}$ ) is the number of inner edges of $G$ with colors $\{2,4\}$ (resp. colors $\{1,3\}$ ). Combining these results and expressing them in terms of parameters of $G^{*}$ gives the following bound for the grid size.

Proposition 4.13. Let $G^{*}$ be a dual-adapted rooted 3,4-map, and let $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ be a dual 4-GS labeling. The increasing function orthogonal drawing algorithm produces a grid drawing of $G^{*}$ on a grid of size $m_{o}^{*} \times m_{e}^{*}$, with

$$
m_{o}^{*} \leq \boldsymbol{f}-\mathbf{d}_{o}^{*}+\mathbf{u}_{o}^{*}, \text { and } m_{e}^{*} \leq \boldsymbol{f}-\mathbf{d}_{e}^{*}+\mathbf{u}_{e}^{*}
$$

where $\boldsymbol{f}$ (resp. $\mathbf{d}_{o}^{*}, \mathbf{d}_{e}^{*}, \mathbf{u}_{o}^{*}, \mathbf{u}_{e}^{*}$ ) is the number of non-root faces (resp. edges of color $\{1,3\}$, edges of color $\{2,4\}$, fully-colored edges with labels $\{1,1,3,3\}$, fully-colored edges with labels $\{2,2,4,4\})$ of $G^{*}$.

In the case where $G$ is a quadrangulation and the 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}$ is even, there are no edges of $G^{*}$ with exactly two colors of the same parity nor any fully-colored edges, hence $m_{o}^{*}$ and $m_{e}^{*}$ are both bounded by $\mathbf{f}^{*}$. This bound matches the grid size of the Bernardi and Fusy's algorithm [BF12] (before the compaction step).

In the case where $G$ is a triangulation, $\mathbf{d}_{o}^{*}+\mathbf{d}_{e}^{*}$ is equal to the number $e_{2}$ of edges of $G$ bearing exactly 2 colors, while $\mathbf{u}_{o}^{*}+\mathbf{u}_{e}^{*}$ is equal to the number $e_{0}$ of edges of $G$ bearing no colors, and the calculation in Section 3.5 gives $\mathbf{d}_{o}^{*}+\mathbf{d}_{e}^{*}=\mathbf{f}^{*}-1+\mathbf{u}_{o}^{*}+\mathbf{u}_{e}^{*}$. In this case, the bound on the half-perimeter of the drawing is simply $m_{o}^{*}+m_{e}^{*} \leq \mathbf{f}^{*}+1$, which matches the bound given by He's algorithm [He93], a bound also achieved by the algorithm in [RNN98] with a different approach.

Remark 4.14. Our drawings have the property that every grid line is occupied by at least one vertex. In that case, letting $\mathbf{v}^{*}$ be the number of non-root vertices, and $s_{h}$ (resp. $s_{v}$ ) be the number of straight horizontal (resp. vertical) edges, An easy argument (see [Bie96]) then ensures that the grid-width is at most $\mathbf{v}^{*}-1-s_{v}$ and the grid-height is at most $\mathbf{v}^{*}-1-s_{h}$. This matches the bounds for $m_{o}^{*}$ and $m_{e}^{*}$ from Proposition 4.13, since $\mathbf{v}^{*}-s_{v}=\mathbf{v}\left(\vec{A}_{o}^{*}\right)$ (contracted edges in $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$ are those counted by $\left.s_{v}\right)$, and similarly $\mathbf{v}^{*}-s_{h}=\mathbf{v}\left(\vec{A}_{e}^{*}\right)$.
Remark 4.15. There is another well-known approach, due to Tamassia [Tam87, Theorem 1], to obtain a grid realization of a given (combinatorial) plane orthogonal drawing. It consists in refining the orthogonal drawing into a (combinatorial) rectangular drawing by suitable insertions of vertices and edges, and then applying He's algorithm [He93] to obtain a grid realization of the rectangular drawing, which yields a grid realization of the original orthogonal drawing. Since every grid-line is occupied by at least one vertex, the bounds of Proposition 4.13 also hold with this strategy. Our approach shows that one can directly apply an increasing function strategy in order to obtain a grid realization, without the preliminary refinement step.

We now state some further bounds on the number of straight edges and grid size in terms of parameters of the planar map solely.

Proposition 4.16. Let $G^{*}$ be a dual-adapted rooted 3,4-map, let $\mathbf{e}^{*}$ be its number of non-root edges, and let $\mathbf{v}_{3}^{*}$ (resp. $\mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}$ ) be its number of vertices of degree 3 (resp. non-root vertices of degree 4).

For any dual 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}^{*}$, the increasing function orthogonal drawing algorithm produces a grid drawing of $G^{*}$ whose number of straight edges is at least $\mathbf{v}_{3}^{*} / 2$ and number of bent edges is at most $4 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}$. Consequently, the semi-perimeter of the grid is at most $\min \left(\mathbf{e}^{*}, \mathbf{e}^{*}+2 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}-\mathbf{v}_{3}^{*}+2\right)$.

Moreover, upon choosing $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ appropriately (linear time), the number of bent edges is at most $3 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}$ and the semi-perimeter of the grid is at most $\min \left(\mathbf{e}^{*}, \mathbf{e}^{*}+\mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}-\mathbf{v}_{3}^{*}+2\right)$.

Proof. The second and third items in Proposition 4.11 imply that, for every vertex of degree 3, the arc with two colors is on a straight edge. Hence the number of straight edges is at least $\mathbf{v}_{3}^{*} / 2$. On the other hand, the first item in Proposition 4.11 ensures that every bent edge turns left from a non-root vertex of degree 4 . Hence, the number of bent edges is at most $4 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}$.

Then it follows from Biedl's bound (see Remark 4.14) that the semi-perimeter is at most

$$
\min \left(2 \mathbf{v}^{*}-2-\mathbf{v}_{3}^{*} / 2,2 \mathbf{v}^{*}-2-\mathbf{e}^{*}+4 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}\right)=\min \left(\mathbf{e}^{*}, \mathbf{e}^{*}+2 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}-\mathbf{v}_{3}^{*}+2\right)
$$

where $\mathbf{v}^{*}=\mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}+\mathbf{v}_{3}^{*}$, and we used $\mathbf{e}^{*}=2 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}+\frac{3}{2} \mathbf{v}_{3}^{*}-2$.
Finally, we observe that for any vertex of degree 4 with contribution 4 to the number of bent edges, one can reduce this contribution to 0 by decreasing by $1(\bmod 4)$ the labels at the 4 corners around that vertex. These operations can be performed simultaneously at all such vertices, and yield a new dual 4-GS labeling for which each vertex of degree 4 has contribution at most 3 to the number of bends. Thus, the number of bent edges after these operations is at most $3 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}$, and the grid semi-perimeter is at most $\min \left(\mathbf{e}^{*}, \mathbf{e}^{*}+\mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}-\mathbf{v}_{3}^{*}+2\right)$.

Remark 4.17. The bound $\mathbf{e}^{*}$ on the semi-perimeter is also satisfied by the algorithm of Biedl and Kant [BK98], which applies to the (larger) family of 2-connected planar maps with vertex degrees at most 4 . However, edges can have up to 2 bends with that algorithm.

Remark 4.18. The bound $3 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}$ for the number of bends of the drawing of $G^{*}$ (in Proposition 4.16) shows that our algorithm produce a drawing at distance at most $3 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}$ from the optimal bend-number over all plane orthogonal drawings of $G^{*}$. Having distance at most $3 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}$ to the optimal bend-number also appears in the orthogonal drawing algorithm given in BLK18 (building on [RNN99]) for 3-connected planar maps with vertex degrees at most 4 (a family which intersects ours but without inclusion of one into the other), where however the optimal bend number can itself be larger than $3 \mathbf{v}_{4}^{*}$.
4.9. Reduction of the grid size. In this subsection we discuss two methods to reduce the grid size of the increasing function orthogonal drawing algorithm. Similarly as for the primal case, these improvements will be obtained by relaxing some constrains for the increasing functions $h_{o}^{*}, h_{e}^{*}$.

Remark 4.19. Throughout this section we work with a fixed dual 4-GS labeling. We note however that in He93, the author discussed some methods to reduce the grid size by changing the transversal structure. We leave as an open question whether these methods can be generalized.

Relaxing the equalities for edges in $B_{o}^{*} \backslash A_{o}^{*}$ and $B_{e}^{*} \backslash A_{e}^{*}$ : The first optimization we present is about relaxing some equalities for the increasing functions $h_{o}^{*}, h_{e}^{*}$. Recall that the increasing functions $h_{o}^{*}$ (resp. $h_{e}^{*}$ ) are defined on all non-root vertices of $G^{*}$, and are constant along edges in $\overrightarrow{A_{o}^{*}}$ (resp. $\overrightarrow{A_{e}^{*}}$ ). We will now relax this condition for some of the edges in $B_{o}^{*} \cap \overrightarrow{A_{o}^{*}}$ (resp. $B_{e}^{*} \cap \overrightarrow{A_{e}^{*}}$ ). Recall that $A_{o}^{*} \subseteq B_{o}^{*}$ and $A_{e}^{*} \subseteq B_{e}^{*}$. A function $g^{*}$ defined on the set of non-root vertices of $G^{*}$ is called $B_{o}^{*}$-increasing (resp. $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing) if it satisfies the following conditions:
(i) $g^{*}(u)=g^{*}(v)$ for every non-root edge $\{u, v\}$ not in $B_{o}^{*}$ (resp. not in $B_{e}^{*}$ ),
(ii) $g^{*}(u) \leq g^{*}(v)$ for every arc $(u, v)$ in $B_{o}^{*} \backslash A_{o}^{*}$ (resp. $B_{e}^{*} \backslash A_{e}^{*}$ ),
(iii) $g^{*}(u)<g^{*}(v)$ for every $\operatorname{arc}(u, v)$ in $A_{o}^{*}$ and (resp. $A_{e}^{*}$ ) and every odd (resp. even) diagonal $\operatorname{arc}(u, v)$.
The only difference between the definition of $B_{o}^{*}$-increasing functions and $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$-increasing functions is that for $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$-increasing functions the requirement $g^{*}(u) \leq g^{*}(v)$ in Condition (ii) would be replaced by $g^{*}(u)=g^{*}(v)$. Hence, any $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$-increasing function is $B_{o}^{*}$-increasing. Similarly, any $\overrightarrow{A_{e}^{*}}$-increasing function is $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing. Hence replacing $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$ and $\vec{A}_{e}^{*}$-increasing functions by $B_{o}^{*}$ and $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing functions in the increasing function algorithm could potentially reduce the grid size, as long as we can show this does not break planarity. Relaxing the inequalities on some diagonal arcs: The second optimization we present is about weakening some inequalities for the $B_{o}^{*}$ and $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing functions $g_{o}^{*}, g_{e}^{*}$. In the increasing function algorithm of Proposition 4.20, the increasing functions $g_{o}^{*}, g_{e}^{*}$ are required to be strictly increasing along the diagonal arcs. We claim that some of these inequalities can be relaxed to weak inequalities.

Let $G^{*}$ be a rooted 3,4 -map, and let $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ be a dual 4 -GS labeling. We call quasi $B_{o}^{*}$-increasing a function $g^{*}$ on the non-root vertices of $G^{*}$ which satisfies all the conditions of $B_{o}^{*}$-increasing functions except that for odd diagonal edges $(u, v)$ the condition $g^{*}(u)<g^{*}(v)$ is replaced by $g^{*}(u) \leq g^{*}(v)$. We define quasi $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing functions similarly.

Note that using quasi $B_{o}^{*}$ and $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing coordinates (instead of strict $B_{o}^{*}$ and $B_{e}^{*}$ increasing coordinates) could lead to a non-planar drawing. Indeed, recall that the condition on diagonal arcs was used to ensure the planarity of the drawing of each non-root face (precisely, these conditions ensure that opposite runs around a face do not intersect). But it is clear that in the example represented in Figure 40(a), the weakening of the inequality for the diagonal $\operatorname{arc}(u, v) \in \overrightarrow{A_{o}^{*}}$ could lead to a violation of planarity (the 4 -run could intersect the 2 -run).

We now identify which diagonals arcs can be weakened. Consider an SPO drawing of a rooted 3,4 -map $G^{*}$ obtained by some $B_{o}^{*}$ and $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing functions $\left(g_{o}^{*}, g_{e}^{*}\right)$. Let $f$ be a non-root face of $G^{*}$ containing a diagonal $\operatorname{arc}(u, v) \in \overrightarrow{A_{o}^{*}}$ (so that the 4 -run and the 2 -run of $f$ are non-empty). Let $C_{4}$ be the lowest point with the same abscissa as $u$ on the drawing of

the 4 -run of $f$, and let $C_{2}$ be the highest point with the same abscissa as $v$ on the drawing of the 2 -run of $f$. The points $C_{2}$ and $C_{4}$ are indicated in Figure 40. We emphasize that $C_{4}$ and $C_{2}$ are geometric features of the embedding of $f$, not features of $f$ itself (in particular, they may correspond to actual vertices on $f$ or just bends of the drawings of edges). It is easy to see that as long as $C_{4}$ is strictly above $C_{2}$, then the inequality $g_{o}^{*}(u)<g_{o}^{*}(v)$ induced by the diagonal $\operatorname{arc}(u, v)$ can be weakened (that is, replaced by the condition $g_{o}^{*}(u) \leq g_{o}^{*}(v)$ ). This is illustrated in Figure 40(b). In this case, we say that the diagonal $\operatorname{arc}(u, v)$ is $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$-weak.

Note that the notion of $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$-weakness for a diagonal arc in $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$ actually depends on the $B_{e}^{*}{ }^{-}$ increasing function $g_{e}^{*}$. Hence this type of optimization needs to be performed one coordinate at a time. Given an SPO drawing of $G^{*}$ where the coordinate functions $\left(g_{o}^{*}, g_{e}^{*}\right)$ are quasi $B_{o}^{*}{ }^{-}$ increasing and $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing respectively, we can define $\vec{A}_{e}^{*}$-weak diagonals similarly as above: for a diagonal $\operatorname{arc}(u, v) \in \vec{A}_{e}^{*}$ in a face $f$ of $G^{*}$ we consider the rightmost point $C_{3}$ with the same ordinate as $u$ on the drawing of the 3 -run of $f$ and the leftmost point $C_{1}$ with same ordinate as $v$ on the drawing of the 1 -run of $f$, and say that the diagonal $(u, v)$ is $\vec{A}_{e}^{*}$-weak if $C_{3}$ is strictly to the left of $C_{1}$. In this case the inequality $g_{e}^{*}(u)<g_{e}^{*}(v)$ can be weakened without breaking planarity.

This suggests the following optimized SPO drawing algorithm:
(1) Compute a (strict) $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing function $\overrightarrow{g_{e}^{*}}$, and find all the $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$-weak diagonal arcs.
(2) Compute a quasi $B_{o}^{*}$-increasing function $g_{o}^{*}$, which is weakly increasing along $\vec{A}_{o}^{*}$-weak diagonal arcs (and strictly increasing along the other diagonal arcs).
(3) Compute a quasi $B_{e}^{*}$-increasing function $g_{e}^{*}$, which is weakly increasing along $\vec{A}_{e}^{*}$-weak diagonal arcs (and strictly increasing along the other diagonal arcs).
(4) Draw the graph $G^{*}$ using the coordinate function $\left(g_{o}^{*}, g_{e}^{*}\right)$.

The above discussion shows that the result of this algorithm is planar (since the validity of the drawing of the inner faces is preserved, and the validity of the drawing of the outer face does not depend on diagonal arcs).

# 5. Additional Remarks and Optimization 

5.1. Variants on the face counting algorithms. The face-counting algorithms given in Sections 3.1 and 4.1 admit some variants that we now describe.

Consider the primal picture first. Let $G$ be an adapted 3,4 -angulation of the square and let $\mathcal{L}$ be a 4 -GS labeling of $G$. In the face-counting algorithm of Section 3.1, each vertex $v$ is placed at the point $\left(\ell_{e}(v), r_{o}(v)\right)$, where $r_{o}(v)$ is the number of inner faces of $B_{o}$ at the right of $P_{o}(v)$ and $\ell_{e}(v)$ is the number of inner faces of $B_{e}$ at the left of $P_{e}(v)$. Given some positive weights associated to each inner face of $B_{o}$ the $B_{e}$, one can consider the vertex placement $\left(\ell_{e}^{\prime}(v), r_{o}^{\prime}(v)\right)$ where $r_{o}^{\prime}(v)$ is the sum of the weights of the inner faces of $B_{o}$ at the right of $P_{o}(v)$ and $\ell_{e}^{\prime}(v)$ is the sum of the weights of the inner faces of $B_{e}$ at the left of $P_{e}(v)$. We claim that this vertex placement lead to a planar drawing of $G$ for any choice of positive weight. This generalizes Theorem 3.1 which corresponds to a weight of 1 for every face. Indeed, one can prove that $\ell_{e}^{\prime}(v)$ is an $\vec{A}_{o}$-increasing function and $r_{o}^{\prime}(v)$ is an $\vec{A}_{s}$-increasing function exactly as before; hence planarity is again a consequence of Theorem 3.3. Similarly one could define some other placement $\left(\ell_{e}^{\prime \prime}(v), r_{o}^{\prime \prime}(v)\right)$ using vertex-counting instead, as they would still be a special case of the increasing function algorithm.

In the dual picture one can also consider variants of the face-counting algorithm by assigning weights to the faces of $B_{o}^{*}$ and $B_{e}^{*}$; or one could define vertex-counting variants as all of these variants fall under the "increasing function" umbrella.

Remark 5.1. The face-counting algorithm of Section 3.1 is somewhat reminiscent of Schnyder's famous drawing algorithm for triangulations [Sch90]. The relation is even closer for a variant of the algorithm that we now present. Let $G$ be an adapted 3,4-angulation of the square with f inner faces, and let $\mathcal{L}$ be a 4 -GS labeling of $G$. Consider the vertex placement given by $\alpha^{\prime}(v)=\left(\ell_{e}^{\prime}(v), r_{o}^{\prime}(v)\right)$, where $r_{o}^{\prime}(v)$ is the number of inner faces of $G$ at the right of $P_{o}(v)$ and $\ell_{e}^{\prime}(v)$ is the number of inner faces of $G$ at the left of $P_{e}(v)$. The analogue of Theorem 3.1 holds for this vertex placement. Indeed it corresponds to one of the face-weighted variants described above (where the weight of a face of $B_{o}$ or $B_{e}$ is the number of faces of $G$ that it contains). Now, for a vertex $v$ of $G$, we can consider the paths $P_{1}(v), \ldots, P_{4}(v)$ in $W_{1}, \ldots, W_{4}$ between $v$ and $v_{4}, v_{1}, v_{2}, v_{3}$ respectively. These paths are non-crossing as proved in [BFL24], and denoting by $r_{i}(v)$ the number of inner faces between $P_{i-1}(v)$ and $P_{i+1}(v)$ one gets $r_{o}^{\prime}(v)=r_{2}(v)+r_{3}(v)$ and $\ell_{e}^{\prime}(v)=r_{3}(v)+r_{4}(v)$. Hence, in barycentric coordinates, one has

$$
\alpha^{\prime}(v)=\lambda_{1}(v) v_{1}+\lambda_{2}(v) v_{2}+\lambda_{3}(v) v_{3}+\lambda_{4}(v) v_{4}
$$

where $v_{1}=(0,0), v_{2}=(0, \mathbf{f}), v_{3}=(\mathbf{f}, \mathbf{f}), v_{4}=(\mathbf{f}, 0)$, and $\lambda_{i}(v)=\frac{r_{i}(v)}{\mathbf{f}}$ for all $i$. This barycentric vertex placement given by the number of inner faces between consecutive Schnyder wood paths is a direct analogue of Schnyder's algorithm [Sch90].
5.2. Triangulating under the 4-connectivity constraint. Given $G$, an adapted 3,4-angulation of the square, it is always possible to add a diagonal in each quadrangular inner face in such a way that the resulting triangulation of the square is adapted. Indeed, it is easy to see that for every quadrangular inner face of $G$, at least one of the two diagonals can be added without creating a separating 3 -cycle. As we now explain, if $G$ is endowed with a 4 -GS labeling then this decision can be made very easily, and moreover the 4 -GS labeling can be maintained all along, in time $O(1)$ for each edge addition, to end with an irreducible triangulation of the square endowed with a 4 -GS labeling.

Let $f$ be a quadrangular inner face of $G$. Let $c$ be a corner incident to $f$, let $e$ be the edge visited after $c$ in clockwise order around $f$, and let $c^{\prime}$ be the corner incident to $e$ opposite to $c$ (i.e., at the other extremity and on the other side). The corner $c$ is called special if the labeljump from $c$ to $c^{\prime}$ is 1 . A corner is called diagonal if it is special and preceded by a non-special corner in clockwise order around $f$. With $c_{1}, c_{2}, c_{3}, c_{4}$ the four corners around $f$ (the index indicating the label), we choose a pair $c_{i}, c_{i+2}$ of opposite corners such that the other corners $c_{i+1}$ and $c_{i-1}$ are not diagonal; such a pair exists since $f$ can not have two consecutive diagonal corners.

We then perform the following operations, see Figure 42 for examples:
(1) decrease by 1 the labels of the special corners around $f$,
(2) insert a diagonal $e$ in $f$ connecting the vertex $v$ at $c_{i}$ and the vertex $v^{\prime}$ at $c_{i+2}$, which creates a new corner at $v$ (resp. at $v^{\prime}$ ), the new corner being considered as the one on the right of $e$, looking from $v$ (resp. from $v^{\prime}$ ),
(3) give label $i$ (resp. $i+2$ ) to the new corner at $v$ (resp. $v^{\prime}$ ).

The conditions of a 4-GS labeling are still satisfied, the crucial point being that the labels of special corners have been decreased in order for Condition (L3) to remain satisfied after adding the diagonal ${ }^{6}$. Moreover, with the notation of Section 3.5, any edge contributing to $\mathbf{d}_{e}$ will keep contributing to $\mathbf{d}_{e}$ all along subsequent edge-additions, and similarly for $\mathbf{d}_{o}$. Hence, the bounds on the grid width and height in Proposition 3.12 are weakly decreasing when adding diagonals by this process (however the actual optimized grid-size may increase).

Let us mention two related previous works. Biedl and Kant have given in [BKK97] a lineartime algorithm that, starting from a planar map with no separating triangle, adds edges incrementally while avoiding the creation of separating triangles, yielding a 4 -connected triangulation of the original planar map. More closely related, in [Fus06] it is shown that, starting from a simple quadrangulation endowed with a separating decomposition, there is a simple process to add diagonals within faces to yield an irreducible triangulation of the square endowed with a transversal structure. What we describe here can be seen as an extension of this process to adapted 3,4 -angulations of the square.
5.3. Bend minimization. In this subsection we explain how to minimize the number of bends in the orthogonal drawings obtained by our increasing function algorithm for rooted 3,4-maps. More precisely, given a dual-adapted rooted 3,4-map $G^{*}$, we want to determine a dual 4-GS structure which leads to a drawing with the least number of bends. For this, we will adapt a method pioneered by Tamassia [Tam87].

Definition 5.2. An SPO drawing of a rooted 3,4-map $G^{*}$ is one-bend if every edge has at most one bend. We use the abbreviation BSPO for such a drawing of $G^{*}$. Two BSPO drawings of $G^{*}$ are called equivalent if they represent the same rooted planar map, and each half-edge has the same direction in both drawings. The combinatorial type of a BSPO drawing is the equivalence class for this relation.

As shown in Figure 43(a), and following Tamassia [Tam87], the combinatorial type of a BSPO drawing can be encoded by assigning values in $\{-1,0,1\}$ at vertex-corners and at edgesides, with value 1 (resp. $0,-1$ ) indicating an angle of $\pi / 2$ (resp. $\pi, 3 \pi / 2$ ). It was shown in [Tam87] that such an assignment encodes a valid combinatorial type (non-empty equivalence class of drawings) if and only if the following conditions are satisfied:

- the sum of values at corners around each vertex $v$ is $2 \operatorname{deg}(v)-4$,
- the sum of edge-side values at each edge is 0 ,
- the sum of values in each inner face is 4 ,
- with the outer contour partitioned by the dangling half-edges, the sum of values in each of the 4 portions is 1 .

Note that these conditions are clearly necessary in order to be able to use the assignment to consistently propagate the directions among \{west, north, east, south\} to all half-edges after fixing the direction of the 4 dangling half-edges.

We call Tamassia assignment such an assignment of values to corners and edge-sides of $G^{*}$. A Tamassia assignment for $G^{*}$ can equivalently be formulated as a flow on a related graph $G^{\boxtimes}$, as shown in Figure 43(b). Let $G^{\boxtimes}$ be the graph obtained from $G^{*}$ by

- placing a blue vertex $v_{f}$ in each face $f$ of $G^{*}$ and tracing a blue edge (joining 2 blue vertices) across each edge of $G^{*}$,
- adding a red edge between blue vertex $v_{f}$ and each of the corner of the face $f$,
- deleting the edges of $G^{*}$.

Given an assignment of a flow in $\{0,1\}$ to each arc of $G^{\boxtimes}$, we call net flow of a vertex $v$ the sum of the flows of the outgoing arcs at $v$, minus the sum of the flows of the incoming arcs at $v$. We call Tamassia flow an assignment of a flow in $\{0,1\}$ to each arc of $G^{\boxtimes}$ such that

- every vertex $v$ of $G^{*}$ has net flow $4-2 \operatorname{deg}(v)$,
- every blue vertex $v_{f}$ has net flow 4 if $f$ is a non-root face, and net flow 1 otherwise.

It is easy to see that the Tamassia assignments are in bijection with the Tamassia flows such that if an arc of $G^{\boxtimes}$ has flow 1 , then the opposite arc has flow 0 ; such Tamassia flows are called valid. We call min-cost a Tamassia flow minimizing the sum of the flow values of arcs on blue edges. Note that the min-cost Tamassia flows are valid and they correspond bijectively to the (combinatorial type of) BSPO drawings of $G^{*}$ minimizing the number of bends. Note that $G^{\boxtimes}$ admits a Tamassia flow (which can be obtained in linear time by applying our drawing algorithm on $G^{*}$ ), hence a min-cost one can be found in time $O\left(n^{3 / 2} \log (n)\right)$, where $n$ is the number of vertices of $G^{*}$ (see [GKHT15] and references therein).

In order to combine the above framework with our algorithm, we need to establish a correspondence between the combinatorial type of the BSPO of $G^{*}$ and the dual 4-GS labelings of $G^{*}$.

As illustrated in Figure 44(a), there is a simple rule to associate to each BSPO drawing of $G^{*}$ a 4-labeling of $G^{*}$, that is, an assignment of a label in $\{1,2,3,4\}$ to each corner of $G^{*}$ : each corner is labeled according to the direction of the half-edge delimiting it on the right side, with labels $1,2,3,4$ corresponding to the directions west, north, east and south respectively. This defines a map $\Phi$ from the set of combinatorial types of the BSPO of $G^{*}$ to the set of 4-labelings of $G^{*}$.

We now consider some particular types of BSPO drawings.
Definition 5.3. A BSPO drawing of a rooted 3,4-map is called right-chiral if it satisfies the following properties:
(A1) no edge leaving a vertex of degree 3 turns left,
(A2) each dangling half-edge has a corner of angle $\pi / 2$ on its right.

Note that Condition (A2) is close to redundant: it is a consequence of (A1) when there is at least one vertex of degree 4 on the outer contour. Moreover, Condition (A1) ensures that the edges connecting two vertices of degree 3 have no bend. Note also that when all vertices have degree 4, any BSPO drawing is right-chiral.

Lemma 5.4. Let $G^{*}$ be a rooted 3,4-map. The mapping $\Phi$ is a bijection between the combinatorial types of right-chiral BSPO drawings of $G^{*}$ and the dual 4-GS labelings of $G^{*}$.

Proof. Let $T$ be a combinatorial type of right-chiral BSPO drawing, and let $\mathcal{L}^{*}=\Phi(T)$. It is easy to check that the sum of label-jumps in clockwise order around each vertex is 4 , and the sum of label-jumps in counterclockwise order around each edge is 4. Moreover, Property (A1) directly translates to the condition (L3*) at edges. It remains to show that there is no label-jump in each of the four outer faces, and that the sum of clockwise label-jumps in each inner face is 4 . Let $F_{i}$ be the set of inner faces, and $F_{o}$ the set of 4 outer faces. For $f \in F_{i} \cup F_{o}$, let $J(f)$ be the sum of clockwise label-jumps around $f$, thus a multiple of 4 . It is actually a positive multiple of 4 for $f \in F_{i}$.

Moreover, (A2) ensures that the clockwise label-jumps across the dangling half-edges are +1 . These are called root label-jumps. Letting $J_{V}$ be the sum of non-root clockwise labeljumps around vertices, we thus have $J_{V}=4|V|-4$. Letting $J_{E}$ be the sum of counterclockwise label-jumps around edges, we have $J_{E}=4|E|$. Each label-jump in counterclockwise around an edge either comes from a non-root label-jump around a vertex, or from a clockwise label-jump around a face. Hence

$$
\sum_{f \in F_{i} \cup F_{o}} J(f)=J_{E}-J_{V}=4|E|-4|V|+4=4\left|F_{i}\right|
$$

by the Euler relation. Since $J(f) \geq 4$ for $f \in F_{i}$, we conclude that $J(f)=4$ for $f \in F_{i}$ and $J(f)=0$ for $f \in F_{o}$. Hence, $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ is a dual 4-GS labeling.

Conversely, for a dual 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}^{*}$, applying the local rule of $\Phi$ allows to determine the directions of all half-edges, yielding a valid combinatorial type $T$ of BSPO drawing. Condition (L3*) then guarantees that (A1) is satisfied, and Condition (A2) is also clearly satisfied, so that $T$ is right-chiral. And by construction the two mappings are inverse of each other.

As a consequence of Lemma 5.4, a rooted 3,4-map $G^{*}$ admits a right-chiral BSPO drawing if and only if it admits a dual 4-GS labeling, and this holds if and only if $G^{*}$ is dual-adapted ${ }^{7}$. In this case, one can easily adapt the approach described above in order to find a right-chiral BSPO drawing of $G^{*}$ having a minimal number of bends. Let us call right-chiral a Tamassia flow of $G^{\boxtimes}$ such that the flow is 0 on every blue arc of $G^{\boxtimes}$ having a vertex of $G^{*}$ of degree 3 on its right. Then the combinatorial types of right-chiral BSPO drawings of $G^{*}$ are in bijection with the right-chiral valid flows of $G^{\boxtimes}$. In this bijection, the combinatorial types of right-chiral BSPO drawings of $G^{*}$ having a minimal number of bends correspond to the min-cost right-chiral Tamassia flows (as before, min-cost minimizes the sum of the flow values of arcs on blue edges). Moreover such a min-cost right-chiral Tamassia flow can be found in time $O\left(n^{3 / 2} \log (n)\right)$, where $n$ is the number of vertices of $G^{*}$.

Finally, recall from Section 4.5 that given a dual 4-GS labeling, a non-root arc $a$ is called special if

$$
(\text { right-init }(a), \text { right-term }(a), \text { left-term }(a), \text { left-init }(a))=(k, k, k+2, k+3)
$$

for some $k \in\{1,2,3,4\}$. We claim that the dual 4-GS labeling corresponding to a min-cost right-chiral Tamassia flow has no special arc. Indeed, if a dual 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ has a special arc $a$, then one can change one of the labels incident to $a$ and get a new dual 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ which corresponds (via $\Phi$ ) to a combinatorial type of right-chiral BSPO with one less bend. This is illustrated in Figure 44(b).

Since the dual 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ corresponding to a min-cost right-chiral Tamassia flow has no special arc, Proposition 4.11 ensures that the BSPO of $G^{*}$ obtained using the increasing function drawing algorithm of Section 4.2 has combinatorial type equal to $\Phi^{-1}\left(\mathcal{L}^{*}\right)$. Thus the obtained BSPO has minimal number of bends among the left-chiral BSPOs of $G^{*}$. This is summarized below.
Proposition 5.5. Let $G^{*}$ be a dual-adapted rooted 3,4-map with $n$ vertices, and let $\mathbf{T}\left(G^{*}\right)$ be the set of combinatorial types of right-chiral BSPO drawings of $G^{*}$. There is an algorithm with time complexity $O\left(n^{3 / 2} \log (n)\right)$ for finding an element $T \in \mathbf{T}\left(G^{*}\right)$ with minimal number of bends. Moreover, letting $\mathcal{L}^{*}=\Phi(T)$ be the associated dual 4-GS labeling, the drawing algorithm of Section 4.2 applied to $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ yields a grid-drawing realization of $T$.
Remark 5.6. Proposition 4.11 ensures that, for any dual 4-GS labeling $\mathcal{L}^{*}$, the drawing algorithm of Section 4.2 applied to $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ always yields a right-chiral BSPO drawing of $G^{*}$ (although its combinatorial type of that BSPO may differ from $\Phi^{-1}\left(\mathcal{L}^{*}\right)$ if $\mathcal{L}^{*}$ has some special edges). Hence the optimal 4-GS labeling of $G^{*}$ in Proposition 5.5 is also the one for which the algorithm of Section 4.2 yields the smallest number of bends (among all possible 4-GS labelings of $G^{*}$ ).

abstract:
We present two graph drawing algorithms based on the recently defined
"grand-Schnyder woods", which are a far-reaching generalization of the
classical Schnyder woods. The first is a straight-line drawing algorithm for
plane graphs with faces of degree 3 and 4 with no separating 3-cycle, while the
second is a rectangular drawing algorithm for the dual of such plane graphs.
  In our algorithms, the coordinates of the vertices are defined in a global
manner, based on the underlying grand-Schnyder woods. The grand-Schnyder woods
and drawings are computed in linear time.
  When specializing our algorithms to special classes of plane graphs, we
recover the following known algorithms: (1) He's algorithm for rectangular
drawing of 3-valent plane graphs, based on transversal structures, (2) Fusy's
algorithm for the straight-line drawing of triangulations of the square, based
on transversal structures, (3) Bernardi and Fusy's algorithm for the orthogonal
drawing of 4-valent plane graphs, based on 2-orientations, (4) Barriere and
Huemer's algorithm for the straight-line drawing of quadrangulations, based on
separating decompositions.
  Our contributions therefore provide a unifying perspective on a large family
of graph drawing algorithms that were originally defined on different classes
of plane graphs and were based on seemingly different combinatorial structures.
